Writing C programs for an embedded systems environment is
significantly different from writing them to run under the control
of an operating system, and this book provides a course on this
very topic!
 
No generative AI (ChatGPT, Gemini, Claude, etc) was used in the
production of this book.
:enotices.
:vnotice.
:vnhd.First Edition, Fall 20226
:note.While this is intended to be a generic :q.C for embedded systems 
primer,:eq. this book is :hp1.heavily:ehp1. targeted towards ELEC 
3040/3050 and covers the prerequisite knowledge required in order to 
succeed in this course.
:coprnote.&copr. Evie Cooper 2026
:coprext.For corrections or comments, please email 
:pv.wec0007@auburn.edu:epv.!
:evnotice.
:preface.Preface
:p.Often times, people hear about C and don't fully understand what all 
it entails. C is a very :hp1.unusual:ehp1. language in the sense that 
it's not well-suited for the writing of large applications (like, for 
example, a web browser or a word processor like Microsoft Word) and is 
more suited for core system programs and firmware.
:p.In the past when computers were large, they were almost universally 
programmed in some form of :hp5.assembly language:ehp5., but writing 
entire large applications in assembler proved to be rather unwieldily.
As a result, the mainframe-era assembler programmers employed tons of 
helpful :hp1.macros:ehp1. to gradually relieve the typing requirements 
of writing plain assembler code.
:p.When C was arranged in the 1970s, it was intended to provide :q.one 
step above assembler language:eq. and strike a balance between 
assembler and a proper high-level language (which, in those days, were 
languages like FORTRAN for math, COBOL for business applications, PL/I 
for user applications, and a whole assortment of now-forgotten 
languages for what C is used for now).
:p.C originated from the :hp1.UNIX operating system:ehp1. and was 
intended to be low-level enough that one could write machine-specific 
code in C, but also write full applications like a text editor in it!
The UNIX authors wanted to run their operating system on a variety of 
computers with distinctly :hp1.different:ehp1. processors -- naturally, 
these processors all used different assembler languages as they all 
used different instruction-set architectures.
:fn.The :hp2.ISA:ehp2. is a topic covered in great detail in the ELEC 
5200/6200 Operating Systems course, but the short summary is this: the 
ISA defines the CPU registers and the CPU instructions (and, therefore, 
the way the assembler language looks).
:efn.
:p.As such, in this book, we will be examining C as a :hp2.high-level 
assembler:ehp2. of sorts; the low-level configuration commands used on 
an STMicroelectronics STM32 will not work on an Atmel AVR or any other 
microcontroller.
:fn.The Arduino line used to use AVRs heavily, but now includes other 
CPU architectures thanks to high-level wrapper libraries like 
:pv.Wiring:epv..
:efn.
Think of this like writing assembler programs with less typing!
:p.Throughout this book, the following typing conventions will be used:
:ul.
:li.Program/variable/library name:
:p.:pv.libc.a:epv.
:li.Program keyword/function name:
:p.:pk.switch:epk.
:li.Source code:
:xmp.int main()
:exmp.
:li.Key program function or idea:
:p.:hp3.Debugging:ehp3.
:li.Vocabulary word:
:p.:hp2.3040/3050:ehp2.
:li.Emphasis:
:p.:hp1.Embedded:ehp1.
:p.:hp5.Lab:ehp5.
:li.Button:
:p.:rk.Run:erk. 
:eul.
:p.This document was formatted with IBM BookMaster 1.4; the images and 
artwork were prepared with :pv.ADMDRAW:epv. (based on an IBM GDDM 3.2 
sample program); the text was edited with Mike Cowlishaw's LEXX. The 
HTML version of this document was formatted with AT&T :pv.B2H:epv..
:p.Thank you Dr. Brown, Dr. Nelson, and Dr. Nelms for their feedback 
during the composition of this book!
:toc.
:figlist.
:tlist.
:body.
:h0.Introduction
:p.This section will provide some background information on the C 
language and the environment in which your programs will run.
:h1 id=environ.Understanding the C Environment
:p.Before getting carried away writing programs, it is helpful to 
understand the environment in which your programs are written and run.
In the olden days, one would just run a command to run the C compiler 
(since, likewise, in those olden days, computers were 
command-line-based systems where you would just type in the name of a 
program you want to run on a command prompt) like :pk.cc:epk. on 
UNIX,:pk.cl:epk. on MS-DOS, so on and so forth; nowadays, we just click 
the Run button and it somehow works!
:h2.Compilation Process
:p.However, it is :hp1.definitely:ehp1. helpful to understand what goes 
on under the hood! When you click that Run (or Debug) button, the 
following programs run in quick succession:
:ol.
:li.:hp2.Preprocessor::ehp2. this program resolves the 
:hp1.preprocessor directives:ehp1. found in the program, like:
:i1.Preprocessor
:ul.
:li.File inclusions
:li.Macros
:li.Conditional compilation
:eul.
:li.:hp2.Compiler::ehp2. this program will take the preprocessed source 
code, then employ a technique that will translate the C into assembler 
language. As such, the target CPU must be supported by the C compiler 
program!
:i1.Compiler
:li.:hp2.Assembler::ehp2. now that the assembler source has been 
produced by the compiler, this program will assemble it and store the 
output in an :hp2.object file.:ehp2. 
:i1.Assembler
:li.:hp2.Linker::ehp2. if the project is comprised of multiple C files,
:fn.Your STM32 C program projects will :hp1.always:ehp1. have multiple 
files!
:efn.
the linker will combine all of the assembled object files into one 
executable; it will also substitute in the memory addresses for 
function calls, variable usages, and other such things. It also adds 
:hp2.libraries:ehp2. into the program.
:i1.Linker
:eol.
:p.The STM32CubeIDE uses the :hp2.GCC:ehp2. C compiler and contains a C 
runtime library -- this library contains a variety of useful C library 
functions that you may have used in the past if you are already 
familiar with C.
:p.If you click Run, the STM32CubeIDE will invoke a program that 
flashes the firmware image file that the linker produced onto the board!
:h3.About the Runtime Library
:p.In the world of C programs that run under the control of an 
:hp1.operating system,:ehp1. the C runtime library
:fn.For the curious, this library is named :pv.libc.a:epv. 
(:pv.libSystem.dylib:epv. on MacOS) on UNIX, and is split into three 
libraries on Windows: :pv.user32.lib:epv., :pv.kernel32.lib:epv., and 
:pv.gdi32.lib:epv..
:efn.
provides all manner of useful functions. You may recognize some of 
these:
:dl tsize=15.
:dt.:pk.malloc():epk. 
:dd.Allocate memory dynamically to a pointer
:dt.:pk.fopen():epk. 
:dd.Open a disk file
:dt.:pk.fread():epk. 
:dd.Read data from a disk file
:dt.:pk.fwrite():epk. 
:dd.Write data to a disk file
:dt.:pk.fclose():epk. 
:dd.Close a disk file
:dt.:pk.system():epk. 
:dd.Run a system command (any shell/terminal command)
:dt.:pk.exit():epk. 
:dd.Leave the program and return to the shell or file browser
:edl.
:p.Unfortunately, :hp5.you cannot use any of these in your STM32 
programs!:ehp5. Because the STM32 isn't running an operating system, 
none of the above functions will work.
:fn.Granted, there is a :pk.malloc():epk. function, but it works 
:hp1.completely differently:ehp1. on the STM32 than it does on an 
operating system!
:efn.
:p.We will explore these runtime library functions later, but they will 
not be amazingly useful. Since this book may also be useful for those 
building their Capstone projects, understanding the library functions 
used for manipulating :hp2.strings:ehp2. will certainly help if you 
wish to have any textual output from your microcontroller (perhaps over 
a serial port or an external character display).
:h2.Debugging Process
:p.When you click on that :rk.Run:erk. or :rk.Debug:erk. button, 
STM32CubeIDE will invoke the above build process, but will then execute 
other tasks based on which of the two buttons you clicked:
:ul.
:li.:rk.Run:erk.
:ol.
:li.Microcontroller is reset
:li.Microcontroller is erased
:li.Program is flashed onto the microcontroller
:fn.By way of the ST-Link chip, found on the underside of the 
STM32L432KCU series boards and found at the top of the STM32F4xxx 
series boards
:efn.
:li.Microcontroller is reset
:eol.
:li.:rk.Debug:erk.
:ol.
:li.Microcontroller is reset
:li.Microcontroller is erased
:li.Program is flashed onto the microcontroller
:li.Microcontroller is reset into trace mode
:li.ST-Link debugger chip starts communicating with :pv.gdb:epv. on 
your computer
:li.The microcontroller CPU is stalled at the reset vector, awaiting 
the clicking of the :rk.Continue:erk. button
:eol.
:eul.
:h2.Object Files and Library Files
:p.The assembler will create object files, which are special files that 
contain a header followed by one or more groups of :hp1.machine 
code:ehp1. and :hp1.data.:ehp1. Any references to variables and 
functions, however, will be left as :q.blanks:eq. to be filled in by 
the linker later (since the linker will know about the memory address 
requirements of either the target microprocessor or operating system).
:i1.Object File
:p.Likewise, one can also create a :hp2.library:ehp2. that contains 
several object files in some kind of collection -- you can then pass 
one of these to the linker and it will automatically fetch variable 
references and functions out of the library collection just as if you 
passed many object files to it.
:i1.Library File
:p.The C runtime library (which provides functions 
like:pk.strcpy:epk.,:pk.memset:epk., and such) is also a, as the name 
implies, a library file linked with every program!
:h0.C Language Primer
:p.This section will provide a basic primer on the C language, syntax, 
and provide some basic code examples that do not require any 
STM32-specific features -- those features will be explored in the next 
section following this one!
:h1.Basic C Syntax
:p.Before learning more advanced topics, let us first understand the 
basic C program structure!
:h2.Comments
:p.A :hp2.comment:ehp2. is a portion of the code that is not compiled; 
it provides you a way to put some textual blurbs in your program
:i1.Comments
:p.You should :hp1.always:ehp1. comment your code! In C, there are two 
ways to define comments, as shown here:
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:xmp.
// This is a simple single-line comment.
 
/* This is a different way to do a single-line comment. */
/* This can also be a
   multi-line comment! */
:exmp.
:figcap.Example comments
:efig.
:lblbox.Why are there two comment types?
:p.In the :q.olden days:eq. of C (like the original K&R C or C89, often 
called :hp1.ANSI C:ehp1.), you could only use the multiline comment 
form!
:p.When C++ came about in the late 1980s, the language designers came 
up with the :pv.//:epv. single-line comment form to alleviate the need 
to type an ending :pv.*/:epv. on every comment.
:p.As one might gather from this, there are :hp2.different versions of 
C!:ehp2.
:ul.
:li.K&R C, from the 1970s
:li.C89, from 1989 (ANSI C, the most commonly-implemented C in embedded 
compilers)
:li.C99, from 1999
:li.C11, from 2011
:li.C23, from 2023 (our STM32CubeIDE C compiler does not support any of 
these features, and they aren't useful to us)
:eul.
:elblbox.
:h2 id=vars.Defining Variables
:p.The simplest thing we can do in a C program is to define some 
:hp2.variables;:ehp2. once we learn how to do this, we will define some 
:hp2.functions:ehp2. (which are just blocks of code that optionally 
return a variable -- if this seems confusing now, it will become clear 
soon).
:p.In C, variables are known by their name and their associated 
:hp1.type.:ehp1. :hp5.The type defines how much memory a variable will 
use!:ehp5. C has the following types:
:ih1.Data types
:ul.
:li.:hp2.integral types:ehp2. which are useful for storing numbers:
:i2.Integral types (char, short, int, long)
:ul.
:li.:pk.char:epk. -- 8-bit
:li.:pk.short:epk. -- 16-bit
:li.:pk.int:epk. -- 32-bit
:li.:pk.long:epk. -- also 32-bit
:fn.The reason that :pk.long:epk.s are 32 bits on the STM32 is because 
the STM32 is a 32-bit ARM CPU (something you probably remember from 
Computer Systems class)
:efn.
 
:eul.
:li.:hp2.Floating-point types:ehp2. for decimal values:
:i2.Floating-point types (float, double)
:ul.
:li.:pk.float:epk. -- basic IEEE-754 floating-point type (32 bits)
:li.:pk.double:epk. -- double-precision floating-point (64 bits)
:eul.
:li.:hp2.Pointer types:ehp2. used to reference objects in memory (this 
will be discussed in great detail later, as these are a difficult topic 
for new C programmers)
:i2.Other types
:li.:hp2.Array types:ehp2. which hold a collection of various items all 
of the same type
:li.:hp2.Structure types:ehp2. which allow you to create singular types 
that hold several sub-variables
:li.The special :hp2.void type:ehp2. used primarily in a function when 
the function has no return type
:eul.
:p.You should also note that the :hp1.integral types:ehp1. can be 
:hp2.signed:ehp2. or :hp2.unsigned:ehp2., wherein you can choose 
whether or not the C compiler will support the usage of negative values 
on a variable or not.
:i1.Signed
:i1.Unsigned
:p.By default, variables are signed unless prefixed by 
the:pk.unsigned:epk. keyword. Here are some example variable 
definitions:
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:xmp.
int myNumber;            // no defined default value
int otherNumber = 12;    // defaults to 12
float result = 12.34;    // a decimal value
unsigned short val;      // example of an unsigned value
:exmp.
 
:figcap.Single variable definitions
:efig.
:p.We will look at actually :hp1.using:ehp1. these variables in a 
future segment.
:h3 id=c99type.C99 Datatypes
:p.The STM32CubeIDE C compiler (GCC) supports the :hp3.C99:ehp3. 
version of C, and therefore lets us use specific variable datatypes 
that have a certain number of bits contained within them (and can 
optionally be signed).
:p.In order to use these, you will need to have the :pk.#include 
<stdint.h>:epk. statement at the top of your program; for more on these 
:hp1.preprocessor directives,:ehp1. see :hdref refid=preproc..
:ih1.C99 datatypes
:i2.uint*
:i2.int*
:table cols='1i 1i 1i'.
:tcap.C99 Datatypes
:thd.
:c.:hp2.Type:ehp2.
:c.:hp2.Bits:ehp2.
:c.:hp2.Signed:ehp2.
:ethd.
:row split=yes.
:c.:pk.uint8_t:epk.
:c.8
:c.yes
:row split=yes.
:c.:pk.int8_t:epk.
:c.8
:c.no
:row split=yes.
:c.:pk.uint16_t:epk.
:c.16
:c.yes
:row split=yes.
:c.:pk.int16_t:epk.
:c.16
:c.no
:row split=yes.
:c.:pk.uint32_t:epk.
:c.32
:c.yes
:row split=yes.
:c.:pk.int32_t:epk.
:c.32
:c.no
:row split=yes.
:c.:pk.uint64_t:epk.
:c.64
:c.yes
:row split=yes.
:c.:pk.int64_t:epk.
:c.64
:c.no
:etable.
:h2 id=sizeof.Getting the Size of Variables
:p.C has a special keyword, :pk.sizeof:epk. that functions somewhat 
like a variable that the compiler will see and replace with the size of 
a variable's memory. You can use this whenever you need to find out how 
big a compound type is (like a :pv.struct:epv. or :pv.union:epv., which 
we will discuss later)!
:p.Usage is as follows:
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:xmp.
int myNumber;
int numSize = sizeof(myNumber);
int intSize = sizeof(int);
:exmp.
 
:figcap.sizeof example
:efig.
:p.The first :pv.sizeof:epv. computes the size of the named variable, 
and the second one computes the size of the generic :pk.int:epk. type.
:h2 id=arrays.Defining Arrays
:p.Arrays in C are :hp5.fixed-size:ehp5. and may or may not have 
default values (just like shown above in the code example for single 
variable definitions).
:i1.Array
:p.Please note that arrays are closely related to a special C data type 
called a :hp2.pointer:ehp2.; see :hdref refid=ptrs. for more 
information. Please familiarize yourself with the basics in this 
section before getting overwhelmed by pointers, since they are a 
notorious stumbling block for novice C programmers!
:p.You declare arrays like this:
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:xmp.
int numbers&lbrk.32&rbrk.;
unsigned char smallValues&lbrk.10&rbrk.;
:exmp.
 
:figcap.Arrays without initialization
:efig.
:h3.Array Initialization
:p.Of course, none of these arrays have any default value
:fn.As a matter of fact, these arrays not only have no default value, 
but will be filled with :hp1.random values:ehp1. that correspond to the 
uncleared reset state of the microcontroller's RAM!
:efn.
that is useful. As such, there are several ways of actually 
initializing an array:
:i2.Initialization
:ol.
:li.:hp2.Immediate Values:ehp2.
:p.This is the easiest way to initialize an array:
:xmp.
int myNumbers&lbrk.&rbrk. = &lbrc.
    5, 10, 15, 20, 25, 30
&rbrc.;
:exmp.
:note.Note that the array size is not present within the square 
brackets -- this array initialization scheme will automatically size 
the array to the number of elements that you type in.
:li.:hp2.String Initialization:ehp2.
:p.Use this format when you are defining a string (which uses the 
:pv.char:epv. type)
:xmp.
char myString&lbrk.&rbrk. = "Demo string";
:exmp.
:li.:hp2.Automatic Zero:ehp2.
:p.When defining an array that you will use later, it is a good idea to 
:hp1.zero the memory:ehp1. it will end up using:
:xmp.
int myNumbers&lbrk.10&rbrk. = &lbrc. 0 &rbrc.;
:exmp.
:li.:hp2.Designated Initializers:ehp2.
:p.Use this feature to assign array values at specific locations in the 
array:
:i3.Designated Initializer
:xmp.
int otherNumbers&lbrk.10&rbrk. = &lbrc.
    &lbrk.5&rbrk. = 5,
    &lbrk.7&rbrk. = 9
&rbrc.
:exmp.
:note.This is a C99 feature.
:eol.
:h2 id=structs.Defining Structures
:p.If you've taken courses on Java in the past (which you will have 
done so if you are a computer engineer), you will be familiar with 
:hp1.classes:ehp1. and all that they entail; A :pv.struct:epv. in C is 
passingly similar to a class that contains only variables.
:i1.Structures (struct)
:p.For those that are confused, a :pv.struct:epv. will let you create a 
:hp5.compound type:ehp5. that itself is a custom data type that 
contains several other variables within it.
:p.Structs are defined as follows, and then instantiated as follows:
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:xmp.
struct MyStruct {              // declare the struct type
    int a;                     // members of the struct...
    char b;
    float c;
};
 
struct MyStruct myInstance;    // instantiate the struct
:exmp.
 
:figcap.Structure definition and instantialization
:efig.
:p.Now, some C programmers will choose to use the :pk.typedef:epk. 
keyword to avoid the need to type :pv.struct:epv. every time the 
structure type is referenced. You can use the :pv.typedef:epv. keyword 
like this:
:i2.typedef
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:xmp.
typedef struct {               // declare the struct type
    int a;                     // members of the struct...
    char b;
    float c;
} MyStruct;
 
MyStruct myInstance;           // instantiate the struct
:exmp.
 
:figcap.Structure typedef usage
:efig.
:p.You can write code like this that actually uses a :pv.struct:epv.:
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:xmp.
struct MyStruct {
    int a;
    char b;
    float c;
};
 
struct MyStruct myInstance;
 
// later on, in a function:
myInstance.a = 5;
myInstance.c = 12.34;
:exmp.
 
:figcap.Structure usage
:efig.
:h2 id=unions.Defining Unions
:p.When you are in a union, you are in a group with other people.
A:pk.union:epk. in C is of a similar idea, except it stores several 
variables overlapping in the same memory space! These have very 
specific uses and are :hp5.not:ehp5. :pv.struct:epv. types, and you 
will likely not need to use these unless you are reading in data sent 
by some external sensor.
:i1.union
:p.The syntax is like this:
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:xmp.
union Tester {                 // declare the union
    int a;                     // members of the union
    char b;
    float c;
} MyStruct;
 
union Tester myDemo;           // instantiate the union
:exmp.
 
:figcap.Union definition syntax
:efig.
:p.Unions are used just like structures, but remember that altering one 
of the :q.members:eq. of the union alters the value of every other 
member!
:h2 id=enums.Defining Enumerations
:p.An enumeration, or :pk.enum:epk. for short, allows you to assign 
user-written names to integer constants. These are particularly useful 
where you may have a variety of numbers that refer to the state of a 
program, but do not wish to recall a number corresponding to every 
state.
:i1.enum
:p.The syntatx to define an :pv.enum:epv. is as follows:
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:xmp.
enum States {
    WAITING, READING, WRITING, CRASHING
};
 
enum States myProgramState;
 
// later on in a function:
myProgramState = WAITING;
:exmp.
 
:figcap.Enum definition and usage syntax
:efig.
:lblbox.Enum Name Limit
:p.Please note something :hp2.extremely important:ehp2. when using 
:pv.enums:epv.: you can only have one occurrence of every word in your 
program!
:p.In other words, you can't define two :pv.enums:epv. that both have 
a:pk.WAITING:epk. enumerator!
:elblbox.
:h2 id=ltrls.Extra Immediate Types
:p.Throughout the examples we have seen so far, the variables have been 
defined as :hp1.plain signed integers:ehp1. or :hp1.character 
strings.:ehp1. In reality, there are many other ways of defining 
so-called :hp2.literals,:ehp2. the value that we assign a variable to 
equal:
:ih1.Immediate types
:ul.
:li.:hp2.Signed decimal&colon.:ehp2. 
:i2.Decimal
:xmp.int x = 5;
:exmp.
:li.:hp2.Unsigned decimal&colon.:ehp2. 
:fn.This employs a :hp2.cast:ehp2., which will be described in more 
detail later.
:efn.
:xmp.unsigned int y = (unsigned int) 1231431;
:exmp.
:li.:hp2.Hexadecimal&colon.:ehp2. 
:i2.Hexadecimal
:xmp.unsigned short demo = 0xAD52;
:exmp.
:li.:hp2.Binary&colon.:ehp2. 
:i2.Binary
:xmp.unsigned char keyValue = 0b11110000;
:exmp.
:li.:hp2.Octal&colon.:ehp2. 
:i2.Octal
:xmp.short testing = 0177;
:exmp.
:li.:hp2.Explicit :pk.long:epk.&colon.:ehp2. 
:i2.Long
:xmp.long myVar = 5423762L;
:exmp.
:li.:hp2.Single character:&colon.:ehp2. 
:i2.Character
:xmp.char val = 'a';
:exmp.
:li.:hp2.Character string&colon.:ehp2. 
:i2.String
:xmp.
char string&lbrk.&rbrk. = "This is a test";
:exmp.
:eul.
:h2 id=funcs.Defining Functions
:p.In C, a :hp2.function:ehp2. is where your actual code goes -- to 
this point, we haven't actually written a line of code that results in 
the CPU having to do :hp1.anything!:ehp1. 
:i1.Function
:p.Let us start simple and create a :pk.void:epk. function that returns 
nothing, and simply performs addition within it:
:fig place=inline width=column frame=rules.
:xmp.
void myFunc() &lbrc.
    int a;       // declare a variable within the function
 
    a = 5;       // assign a value to the variable
    a = a + 2;   // add 2 to the variable
 
&rbrc.
:exmp.
 
:figcap.Basic function with no parameters or return
:efig.
:p.Something important to note is the critical concept of :hp2.variable 
scope:ehp2. -- this is the term that refers to the regions wherein, if 
you declare a variable, it can be used later. The general way to 
remember this is:
:i2.Scope
:lq.
:p.Variables declared within the body of a function will not be usable 
outside of the function, and variables declared outside of any function 
(such as at the top of the C source file) will be usable by 
:hp1.any:ehp1. function (and may be modified by any function too). :elq.
:p.Take the following function example that references variables that 
are :hp5.out-of-scope:ehp5.:
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:xmp.
void function1() {
    int x = 5;             // declare x
    x++;                   // increment x by 1
}
 
void function2() {
    x = 12;                // x is not in the scope
}
:exmp.
:figcap.Out-of-scope variable usage demonstration
:efig.
:p.The assignment of :pv.x:epv. in the second function will result in 
the displaying of a syntax error message by the compiler!
:h3 id=return.Return Types
:p.A function can also have a :hp2.return type:ehp2. -- the above 
examples use the :pk.void:epk. return type, which means there is 
:hp1.no:ehp1. return type. It is best to examine the syntax to define a 
function with a return type through example:
:i2.Return type
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:xmp.
int giveNumber() {
    return 5;
}
:exmp.
 
:figcap.Return-type function definition
:efig.
:lblbox.Returning Arrays
:p.Many novices wonder if they can return arrays. You can, but you 
cannot return :hp2.immediate arrays:ehp2., and you are really returning 
a :hp2.pointer.:ehp2. One may imagine a function like this:
:xmp.
char* giveString() {
    return "This is a sample";
}
:exmp.
:p.This will, however, :hp1.not:ehp1. work at all -- the value returned 
from the :pv.giveString():epv. function will actually be the memory 
address of the :pv."This is a sample":epv. string. This will result in 
the clobbering of the return address on the stack, resulting in a 
program hang.
:p.If this is confusing, don't worry! Just remember to not ever try to 
return an array!
:elblbox.
:h3.Function Parameters
:p.Functions can also have :hp2.parameters:ehp2. that allow you to pass 
immediates and variables into a function. If you pass a variable, its 
contents will be :hp1.copied:ehp1. into the function; as such, the 
value passed into the function should not be modified. To modify a 
value, you will need to use a pointer (which will be described later).
:i2.Parameters
:p.Here are a few function definitions that take parameters:
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:xmp.
int addTogether(int a, int b) {
    return a + b;
}
 
int addThree(int numbers&lbrk.&rbrk.) {
    return numbers&lbrk.0&rbrk. + numbers&lbrk.1&rbrk. + numbers&lbrk.2&rbrk.;
}
 
struct MyStruct {
    int intInStruct;
};
 
 
int extractStruct(struct MyStruct entry) {
    return entry.intInStruct;
}
:exmp.
 
:figcap.Functions with parameters (also array and structure)
:efig.
:h3 id=callfnc.Calling Functions
:p.The point of functions is to :hp2.call:ehp2. them, or invoke them.
Functions with no return type
:fn.That is, the :pk.void:epk. type.
:efn.
are called slightly differently than functions with a return type.
:p.Here is a sample of calling some functions :hp1.without:ehp1. return 
types:
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:xmp.
void callee() {
    // this function body would do something
}
 
void caller() {
    callee();                        // call the function
}
:exmp.
 
:figcap.Return-type function definition
:efig.
:p.Here is a sample of calling some functions with return types:
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:xmp.
int addTogether(int a, int b) {
    return a + b;
}
 
int addThree(int numbers&lbrk.&rbrk.) {
    return numbers&lbrk.0&rbrk. + numbers&lbrk.1&rbrk. + numbers&lbrk.2&rbrk.;
}
 
void callThem() {
    int sum;                         // will hold the sum
 
    sum = addTogether(2, 4);         // immediate parameters
 
    int num1 = 8;
    int num2 = 16;
    sum = addTogether(num1, num2);   // variable parameters
 
    int numbers&lbrk.&rbrk. = {5, 10, 15};     // our array
    sum = addThree(numbers);         // array parameter
}
:exmp.
 
:figcap.Calling functions with return types
:efig.
:h3.The Main Function
:p.Your program will :hp5.always:ehp5. start with a function 
named:pk.main:epk., with an :pv.int:epv. return type. This is defined 
as follows:
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:xmp.
void somecode() {
    // this function body would do something
}
 
int main() {                         // program starts here
    somecode();
}
:exmp.
 
:figcap.Main function definition
:efig.
:p.No matter how complicated your program may be, it will 
:hp5.always:ehp5. start in the main function -- this cannot be changed!
:h3 id=inline.Inline Functions 
:p.For optimization reasons, the C99 version of the language permits 
you to create :hp2.inline functions:ehp2. that results in the assembler 
code for the function being deposited straight into the code that 
called the function. Here is an example inline function: 
:i1.inline
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:p.Source code in file:
:xmp.
inline int add(int a, int b) {
    return a + b;
}
 
int main() {
    display(add(5, 2)); // NOTE: display() is not a real function
}
:exmp.
:p.Effective code:
:xmp.
int main() {
    display(5 + 2);
}
:exmp.
 
:figcap.Inline function definition
:efig.
:h1 id=control.Flow Control
:p.Inevitably, in the course of writing your program, you will want to 
add in :hp1.branches:ehp1. for decision-making. In C, you have a 
variety of :hp5.control flow statements:ehp5. you can write into your 
program:
:ul.
:li.:pk.if:epk. statements, for checking the status of one or more 
variable and running a block of code :hp1.once:ehp1.
:li.:pk.while:epk. statements, for repeatedly checking the status of 
one or more variables and running a block of code :hp1.once or more 
than once:ehp1.
:li.:pk.switch/case:epk. statements, for making a :q.lookup table:eq. 
and running a small amount of code :hp1.once:ehp1. 
:eul.
:h2 id=ifstmt.If Statements
:p.The simplest of the control flow statements is the first one in the 
above list, the :pk.if:epk. statement. This statement is of the 
following syntax:
:i1.if
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:xmp.
if(100 > 10) {  // this is the "condition"
    // this code will always run
}
:exmp.
 
:figcap.Example if statement definition
:efig.
:p.This can, of course, be more complex; please see 
:hdref refid=elseif..
:h3.Conditions
:p.The :hp2.condition:ehp2. within the :pk.if:epk. statement body 
contains a comparison operation, which are of the following forms:
:i2.Conditions
:dl tsize=15.
:dt.:pk.a == b:epk. 
:dd.Does :pv.a:epv. equal :pv.b:epv.?
:dt.:pk.a != b:epk. 
:dd.Does :pv.a:epv. not equal :pv.b:epv.?
:dt.:pk.a < b:epk. 
:dd.Is :pv.a:epv. less than :pv.b:epv.?
:dt.:pk.a > b:epk. 
:dd.Is :pv.a:epv. greater than :pv.b:epv.?
:dt.:pk.a <= b:epk. 
:dd.Is :pv.a:epv. less than or equal to :pv.b:epv.?
:dt.:pk.a >= b:epk. 
:dd.Is :pv.a:epv. greater than or equal to :pv.b:epv.?
:dt.:pk.a:epk. 
:dd.Is :pv.a:epv. greater than :pv.0:epv.?
:edl.
:p.
:p.The condition may use one or two constants or variables.
:fn.If this is confusing: you can compare a variable against a 
constant, two variables against each other, or two constants against 
each other (this is very rarely done, though)
:efn.
:h3.Multiple Conditions/Logical Operators
:p.In addition to having a single condition statement, you can also 
have :hp1.several:ehp1. condition statements if you choose to use 
:hp2.logical operators:ehp2. like these:
:i2.Logical Operators
:dl tsize=15.
:dt.:pk.a && b:epk. 
:dd.And
:dt.:pk.a || b:epk. 
:dd.Or
:dt.:pk.a ! b:epk. 
:dd.Not
:edl.
:i2.Logical Operators
:p.You would use them like this:
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:p.And:
:xmp.
if((a == b) && (c != d)) {
    // use parenthesis adequately to avoid confusion!
}
:exmp.
:p.Or:
:xmp.
if(a == b) || c) {
    // this is if a equals b and c is greater than zero
}
:exmp.
:p.Not:
:xmp.
if(!a && !(b < c)) {
    // the distributive property applies, like DeMorgan's Theorem
}
:exmp.
 
:figcap.If statements with logical operators
:efig.
:h3 id=elseif.Else-If Statements
:p.Inevitably, you may want to have a decision that has more than one 
exit (up to this point, all of the statements we have looked at contain 
only one exit) -- you can create these by using the :pk.else if:epk. 
and :pk.else:epk. statements.
:i2.else If
:i2.else
:p.This looks like this:
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:xmp.
if(decision1) {
    // this code runs if "decision1" is true
}
else if(decision2) {
    // this code runs if "decision2" is true
}
else if(decision3) {
    // this code runs if "decision3" is true
}
else {
    // this runs if none of the above decisions are true
}
:exmp.
 
:figcap.Full If statement definition
:efig.
:p.The purpose of :pk.else if:epk. and :pk.else:epk. is to allow you to 
have a :hp1.multiple-way-out decision:ehp1. given a single :pk.if:epk. 
statement.
:h2 id=while.While Statements
:p.If you want to create a :hp3.loop,:ehp3. you will want to use 
a:pk.while:epk. loop (or a :pk.for:epk. loop, described in 
:hdref refid=forloop.).
:i1.while
:p.A :pk.while:epk. loop will execute a block of code as long as a 
given :hp1.condition:ehp1. (just like in an :pk.if:epk. statement) 
remains true. By default, the code is ran :hp5.after:ehp5. the 
condition check, but we will examine a version of a :pk.while:epk. 
statement that runs the code :hp5.before:ehp5. the check.
:p.The syntax of a :pk.while:epk. statement is as follows:
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:xmp.
int a = 1;
 
while(a == 1) {
    if(key == 12345) {
        a = 0;
    }
    // run this forever until the "key" is set to 12345 elsewhere
}
:exmp.
:figcap.While statement definition
:efig.
:p.In order to construct a :hp3.loop:ehp3., you can have an inequality 
check for the condition statement:
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:xmp.
int a = 0;
 
while(a < 10) {
    // code here will run 10 times
    a--;
}
:exmp.
:figcap.While statement loop
 
:efig.
:p.In this example, :pv.a++:epv. increments the variable :pv.a:epv. by 
one. :hp2.For more information,:ehp2. see :hdref refid=math.. :hp5.You 
will probably want to go read that section and then come back!:ehp5.
:p.A :pk.while:epk. statement runs forever as long as the statement is 
:q.true.:eq. 
:fn.In C, a statement is :q.true:eq. as long as it evaluates to a value 
that isn't zero. As such, :pv.while(1):epv. will result in an infinite 
loop!
:efn.
:h3.Premature Exiting
:p.If at any point you wish to either :hp1.exit from a loop:ehp1. or 
:hp1.jump to the next iteration:ehp1., you can use the following two 
keywords to do this:
:i1.break
:i1.continue
:ul.
:li.:pk.break:epk.
:li.:pk.continue:epk. 
:eul.
:p.Here is a complex :pv.while:epv. loop that uses both of these:
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:xmp.
int a = 0;
 
while(a < 10) {
    if(a == 5) {
        break;              // leave early on the 5th run
    }
    if(a == 6) {
        continue;
    }
    a++;                    // increment the loop counter
}
:exmp.
:figcap.While loop with break/continue
:efig.
:h2 id=dowhile.Do-While Loops
:p.If you wish to construct a loop that :hp1.runs code first:ehp1. then 
checks the condition, you can use a :pk.do-while:epk. loop. The syntax 
is relatively similar to a standard :pv.while:epv. loop:
:i1.do
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:xmp.
int a = 0;
 
do {
    something();
    a++;
} while(a < 10);
:exmp.
:figcap.Do-while loop example
:efig.
:h2 id=forloop.For Statements
:p.The purpose of a :pk.for:epk. statement is primarily to construct 
loops that will run for a specific number of cycles, or until a certain 
condition has been met; it provides a more feature-rich version of 
a:pk.while:epk. statement. The syntax is follows:
:i1.for
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:xmp.
void forDemo() {
    for(variable; condition; increment) {
        // this is the body
    }
}
:exmp.
 
:figcap.For statement definition
:efig.
:p.The three parts of the :pk.for:epk. statement are as follows:
:ol.
:li.:pk.variable:epk. defines the reset term for the variable; this 
sets the variable that counts how many iterations the loop runs to the 
starting value. With C99, you can also :hp1.define:ehp1. the variable 
and its associated type here.
:p.Example: :pv.i = 0:epv.
:li.:pk.condition:epk. is the condition statement that specifies when 
the loop will stop running. This is the same as what you would find in 
a :pk.while:epk. statement.
:p.Example: :pv.i < 10:epv.
:li.:pk.increment:epk. specifies a single line of code that will run 
to, usually, increase the variable (though you can also call a function 
that increments the variable).
:p.Example: :pv.i++:epv. 
:eol.
:p.In this example, :pv.i++:epv. increments the variable :pv.i:epv. by 
one. :hp2.For more information,:ehp2. see :hdref refid=math.. :hp5.You 
will probably want to go read that section and then come back!:ehp5. 
:lblbox.Too Many Semicolons!
:p.Interestingly enough, you can actually :hp1.omit:ehp1. any of the 
terms within a :pk.for:epk. loop. This is actually one of the ways you 
can create an infinite loop! It looks like this:
:xmp.for(;;) {
    // body
}
:exmp.
:elblbox.
:p.Putting it all together, here are sample :pk.for:epk. statements:
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:xmp.
void forDemo() {
    int i;
    int sum;
 
    // basic for loop with a predefined variable
    for(i = 0; i < 10; i++) {
        sum = sum + i;
    }
 
    // for loop with a variable defined in-statement
    for(int j = 10; j > 0; j--) {
        sum = sum - j;
    }
    // for loop with a dropped incrementor
    for(int k = 0; k < 10;;) {
        sum = sum + k;
        k++;
    }
}
:exmp.
 
:figcap.For statement examples
:efig.
:h2 id=switch.Switch Statements
:p.Rather than having tons of back-to-back :pk.else if:epk. statements, 
you can use a :pk.switch:epk. statement to streamline the process!
:i1.switch
:i2.case
:p.A :pk.switch:epk. statement is contains a :q.body:eq. that itself 
has one or more :pk.case:epk. statements that actually perform actions.
The definition is as follows:
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:xmp.
void caseDemo() {
    switch(myVariable) {
    case 1:
        doFunction1();
        break;
    case 2:
        doFunction2();
        break;
    case 3:
    case 4:
        doFunction3and4();
        break;
    default:
        doFunctionOthers();
    }
}
:exmp.
 
:figcap.Switch/case statement definition
:efig.
:p.The purpose of the :pk.break:epk. statement is to provide an 
:hp2.exit:ehp2. from the :pk.case:epk. block it is found in. If you 
forget to code in the :pk.break:epk. statements for your:pk.case:epk.s, 
you will end up accidentally running every code block for every case!
You can, of course, do some interesting things with this -- see the 
call to :pv.doFunction3and4():epv. for an example of two back-to-back 
cases that result in the same code chunk being executed.
:h1 id=math.Math Operations
:h2.Arithmetic Operations
:p.Though you saw variable addition in :hdref refid=callfnc., you may 
also wish to know the other arithmetic operations that you can perform.
Here is a list of them:
:i1.Arithmetic
:dl tsize=15.
:dt.:pk.a + b:epk. 
:dd.Addition
:dt.:pk.a - b:epk. 
:dd.Subtraction
:dt.:pk.a * b:epk. 
:dd.Multiplication
:dt.:pk.a / b:epk. 
:dd.Division
:fn.Note! This is :hp2.integer division:ehp2. if the first value is an 
integer! For :hp2.decimal division:ehp2., the numerator must be a 
floating-point variable or immediate!
:efn.
:dt.:pk.a % b:epk. 
:dd.Modulus
:dt.:pk.a++:epk. 
:dd.Increment by 1
:dt.:pk.a--:epk. 
:dd.Decrement by 1
:edl.
:h3.Pre or Post Increment?
:p.Often times, the increment/decrement operators are used to great 
effect in :pv.while:epv.-loop containing blocks like this:
:i2.Increment/Decrement Pre/Post
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:xmp.
int a = 0;
int coolArray&lbrk.10&rbrk. = { ... };
 
while(a < 10) {
    doSomething(coolArray&lbrk.a++&rbrk.);
}
:exmp.
:figcap.Post-increment loop example
:efig.
:p.In this example, :pv.a:epv. will be incremented :hp2.after:ehp2. it 
is read and used for the array index for :pv.coolArray:epv. there in 
the loop body. This ensures that the loop will properly exit without 
running out-of-bounds.
:p.However, you can change the position of that :pk.++:epk. operator to 
make it such that reading the variable returns the :hp5.current:ehp5. 
value:
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:xmp.
int result = 0;
int numbers&lbrk.&rbrk. = {1, 2, 3, 4, 5};
 
void demo() {
    int i = 0;
    for(i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
        result += ++numbers&lbrk.5&rbrk.;
    }
}
:exmp.
:figcap.Pre-increment loop example
:efig.
:h2 id=bitwise.Bitwise Operations
:p.If you wish to preform :hp2.binary operations,:ehp2. you can use 
bitwise operations! These let you manipulate individual bits within a 
variable, and will be :hp1.amazingly:ehp1. useful later when we begin 
manipulating STM32 peripherals!
:p.Here are the bitwise operators:
:dl tsize=15.
:dt.:pk.a & b:epk. 
:dd.:pv.a:epv. AND :pv.b:epv.
:dt.:pk.a | b:epk. 
:dd.:pv.a:epv. OR :pv.b:epv.
:dt.:pk.a &caret. b:epk. 
:dd.:pv.a:epv. XOR :pv.b:epv.
:dt.:pk.a << b:epk. 
:dd.Shift :pv.a:epv. left :pv.b:epv. times
:dt.:pk.a >> b:epk. 
:dd.Shift :pv.a:epv. right :pv.b:epv. times
:dt.:pk.a ~ b:epk. 
:dd.:pv.a:epv. NOT :pv.b:epv. 
:edl.
:p.To actually use these bitwise operators, please examine the 
following sample. The :hp1.binary literal:ehp1. format is described in 
:hdref refid=ltrls..
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:xmp.
char a = 0b0001 & 0b0100; // a = 0101
char b = 0b0111 | 0b1000; // b = 1111
char c = ~0b1010;         // c = 0101
:exmp.
:figcap.Bitwise operations and binary literals
:efig.
:h2.Shorter Operations
:p.Sometimes, you may have a statement like this:
:xmp.sum = sum + 2;
:exmp.
:p.This is actually the :hp2.long:ehp2. way to write this! It can be 
abbreviated as such:
:xmp.sum += 2;
:exmp.
:p.The following other operators exist:
:dl tsize=15.
:dt.:pk.a += b:epk. 
:dd.Addition
:dt.:pk.a -= b:epk. 
:dd.Subtraction
:dt.:pk.a *= b:epk. 
:dd.Multiplication
:dt.:pk.a /= b:epk. 
:dd.Division
:dt.:pk.a %= b:epk. 
:dd.Modulus
:dt.:pk.a |= b:epk. 
:dd.OR
:dt.:pk.a &caret.= b:epk. 
:dd.XOR
:dt.:pk.a &tilde.= b:epk. 
:dd.NOT
:edl.
:h1 id=ptrs.Pointers
:p.The most difficult thing in C to grasp, by far, is the concept of a 
:hp2.pointer.:ehp2. While there are many difficult and convoluted ways 
of describing a pointer, I have narrowed it down to three that should 
:q.click:eq. in your brain and provide a decent synopsis of what these 
mythical types are:
:i1.Pointer
:ol.
:li.A pointer is a special type of variable that stores a memory 
address to another variable as its contents.
:li.A pointer can be used to access any location in memory when 
assigned to a value that itself is a numeric immediate containing a 
memory address.
:li.:hp2.Dereferencing:ehp2. a pointer lets you work with the contents 
of memory located at the memory address stored in the pointer, may it 
be reading or writing.
:eol.
:p.Since we are targeting an STM32 and will therefore need to 
:hp1.directly:ehp1. access memory to control various things like I/O 
configuration registers and whatnot, mastering pointers will be 
:hp5.very:ehp5. important!
:h2.Defining and Using Pointers
:p.Pointers can be defined simply by inserting a :pk.*:epk. between a 
variable's type definition and its name. There are actually 
:hp1.three:ehp1. different ways to define a pointer, all of which are 
valid:
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:xmp.
int* x;
int *y;
int * z;
:exmp.
:figcap.Basic pointer definitions
:efig.
:lblbox.The Great Pointer Debate
:p.Did you know that there is :hp1.no:ehp1. consensus on which of the 
three pointer definition styles is correct? Some argue that the first 
is correct, because the second looks like the :hp1.dereference:ehp1. 
operator (we will look at that next) and the third looks like 
multiplication! Others argue that the second is correct because you 
can't define multiple pointers on the same line if you use the first or 
third style! The truth is that :hp1.all:ehp1. of them are correct, and 
you can use whichever one you want!
:p.I, personally, use the first style on account of the explanation 
given about it looking rather similar to the dereferencing operator.
:elblbox.
:h3.Using Pointers
:p.Now that you have seen how to define pointers, let us see how they 
are used. The simplest thing you can do with a pointer is fill it with 
the memory location of an already-defined variable. Once our pointer is 
defined, we will then manipulate the variable it points to 
:hp1.through:ehp1. the pointer. This looks like this:
:i2.Address-of operator
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:xmp.
int x = 50;
int* y = &x;        // & means "take the address of"
 
// note this function takes an int, not an int pointer!
void print(int number) {
    // magically show the "number" on the screen somehow...
}
 
void pointerDemo() {
    x = 51;         // change x to 51, y remains the same
    print(*y);      // display what y points to, which is x = 51
    *y = 52;        // y points to x and just changed x to 52
    print(*y);      // display what y points to, which is x = 52
    print(x);       // this also displays 52
    print(&x)       // print the memory address of x, 0x20000000
    print(&y)       // print the memory address of y, 0x20000004
}
:exmp.
:figcap.Pointer usage example
:efig.
:p.Whenever you see :pk.*y:epk., this is called 
:hp5.dereferencing.:ehp5. 
:i2.Dereferencing
:p.As you can see, both :pv.x:epv. and :pv.y:epv. are themselves 
:hp5.variables:ehp5.; pointers are definitely a type of their own
:fn.As in, pointers are a distinct type in the same way that integral 
types, floating-point types, and function types are distinct types.
:efn.
, but that does not mean they don't have a memory address!
:lblbox.Why are the memory addresses what they are?
:p.On our STM32, the ROM starts at address :pv.0x08000000:epv. (this is 
where our program is) and the RAM starts at :pv.0x20000000:epv. Since 
we defined two variables, of the type :pk.int:epk., both consume 32 
bits of memory (or, 4 bytes). Therefore, :pv.x:epv. is at 
:pv.0x20000000:epv. and :pv.y:epv. is at :pv.0x20000004:epv.; if we had 
another variable, it would be at :pv.0x20000008:epv. (because the STM32 
uses 32-bit memory addresses, and each one results in 4 bytes of RAM 
being used).
:elblbox.
:p.Likewise, as you can see in the above sample, pointers are treated 
as variables when prepended by the :pk.*:epk. symbol; otherwise, they 
will be treated as pointers!
:h3.Strings and Arrays as Pointers
:p.Strings are a special hybridization of arrays and pointers that are 
used to store blocks of text. When you define a string, like this:
:i2.Strings
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:xmp.char* myMessage = "this is a string";
 
:exmp.
:figcap.String definition example
:efig.
:p....you are actually defining :pv.myMessage:epv. as a pointer whose 
memory address numeric value is equal to the memory location where that 
message will eventually be stored. Likewise, you can define strings and 
arrays both like this (using the pointer syntax :hp1.or:ehp1. the array 
syntax):
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:xmp.
char myMessage&lbrk.&rbrk. = "this is array-style";
char* myOtherMessage = "this is pointer-style";
:exmp.
:figcap.Array-style string definition example
:efig.
:p.Likewise, we can define an array and then create a pointer to the 
first element of the array:
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:xmp.
int myNumbers&lbrk.&rbrk. = { 1, 2, 3, 4, 5 };
int* numbersPointer = &myNumbers;
 
void pointerDemo() {
    print(myNumbers&lbrk.0&rbrk.);            // 1
    print(*numbersPointer);         // also 1
}
:exmp.
:figcap.Array/pointer intermixing
:efig.
:p.This may not seem useful now, but this will become :hp1.very:ehp1. 
useful later on when we get to pointer arithmetic; see 
:hdref refid=ptrmth. for more about this.
:h3.Structure Pointers
:p.You can also define pointers to structures, but this changes how you 
use the structure. Just like you use the dereference operator to access 
a plain pointer to a plain variable, you must also dereference the 
structure pointer. However, there are actually :hp1.two:ehp1. operators 
for accessing the fields of a structure pointer! See the following 
example:
:i2.Structure pointer
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:xmp.
struct DemoStruct {
    int a;
    int b;
};
 
struct DemoStruct myStruct;
 
void structPointerDemo() {
    myStruct.a = 5;
    myStruct.b = 10;
 
    struct DemoStruct* myStructPointer;
 
    print(myStruct.a);                    // 5
    print(*(myStructPointer).a);          // also 5
 
    (*myStructPointer).a = 20;
    (*myStructPointer).b = 40;
    print(myStruct.a);                    // 20
    print(*(myStructPointer).a);          // also 20
 
    myStructPointer->a = 100;             // other deref style
    print(myStruct.a);                    // 100
    print(myStructPointer->a);            // also 100
}
:exmp.
:figcap.Structure pointer example
:efig.
:h2 id=ptrmth.Pointer Arithmetic
:p.One of the more confusing things about pointers is that you can 
perform arithmetic operations on them! This may not seem very useful to 
us since we are not really handling strings on our STM32 (and you 
normally see pointer arithmetic used in code that handles strings), but 
it is still a useful tool to have in your belt nonetheless.
:i2.Pointer arithmetic
:p.Something :hp3.critical:ehp3. to remember when using pointer 
arithmetic is to make sure that you always stay :hp2.aligned!:ehp2. If 
you have an array of :pk.int:epk.s, and you march through the array one 
byte at a time, you will not properly read the array since you'll be 
reading 3/4ths of an :pk.int:epk.!
:p.The following graphic shows two :pk.int:epk.s stored, back to back 
on a little-endian
:fn.The STM32 is :hp3.little-endian,:ehp3. meaning that multi-byte 
types (like :pk.int:epk.) are stored such that the lowest fourth of the 
four-byte :pk.int:epk. comes first.
:efn.
system:
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:xmp.int a = 12;
int b = 34;
:exmp.
:cgraphic.
&Ul.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Td.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Td.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Td.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Td.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Td.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Td.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Td.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Ur.
&Lv. 00 &Lv. 00 &Lv. 00 &Lv. 0C &Lv. 00 &Lv. 00 &Lv. 00 &Lv. 22 &Lv. content
&Tr.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tu.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tu.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tu.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Ju.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tu.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tu.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tu.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tl.
&Lv.         a         &Lv.         b         &Lv. variable
&Ll.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tu.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lr.
:ecgraphic.
:figcap.Storage of integers
:efig.
:p.Fortunately, any time you add or subtract to a pointer (either by 
using the increment/decrement operation or by adding or subtracting an 
integer to a pointer), the C compiler will automatically figure out the 
alignment for you.
:p.Going back to the above graphic, if you created a pointer to 
:pv.a:epv. then incremented it by one (:pv.a++:epv.), you should be 
moved over :hp5.four:ehp5. bytes such that the address increases by an 
entire :pk.int:epk. at a time.
:note.If you :hp1.cast:ehp1. the pointer type for your pointer to 
:pv.a:epv. to something that :hp1.isn't:ehp1. an :pk.int:epk. (like 
a:pk.char:epk.), you will then be responsible for ensuring correct 
alignment (because incrementing the :pk.char:epk.-casted pointer to 
:pv.a:epv. by 1 will not fully shift the memory address over into the 
next :pk.int:epk.). For more information on this, see 
:hdref refid=casts..
:p.Here is an example of scanning through an array using both the 
standard array syntax and by using pointer arithmetic:
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:xmp.
int myNumbers&lbrk.&rbrk. = { 1, 2, 3, 4, 5 };
void scan() {
    for(int i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
        print(myNumbers&lbrk.i&rbrk.);
    }
    for(int i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
        print(*(myNumbers + i));          // array-as-a-pointer
    }
}
:exmp.
:figcap.Pointer arithmetic array-scan example
:efig.
:p.I'm sure you have several questions about the code, specifically 
:q.why is the stop address not five times four:eq. and :q.why does 
:pv.i:epv. not increase by 4 every iteration?:eq. The answer to this is 
that when you perform pointer arithmetic, as mentioned before, you 
:hp5.must:ehp5. always remain aligned; the C compiler does the 
alignment for you such that you move only one array element at a time!
Each :pk.int:epk. takes 4 bytes of memory, so the compiler must account 
for the true size of the array and also step forwards one :pk.int:epk. 
at a time. You, on the other hand, only have to move one index at a 
time and the compiler figures out the rest!
:h2.Pointers as Arguments
:p.Sometimes, you may wish to write a function that actually 
:hp1.modifies:ehp1. one or more of its arguments! With pointer 
arguments, you can actually do this relatively easily. Since you pass 
the memory address into the function, none of the function-calling 
mechanics actually touch the variable that you are passing the pointer 
to. Examine the following code block for an example of this:
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:xmp.
int myNumber = 5;
 
void increase(int* input) {
    *input += 2;
}
 
void demo() {
    print(myNumber);              // 5
    increase(&myNumber);
    print(myNumber);              // 7
}
:exmp.
:figcap.Function with a pointer argument
:efig.
:p.Of course, the :pk.&:epk. operator passes a pointer to 
:pv.myNumber:epv. into the :pv.increase():epv. function body.
:h2 id=fnptr.Function Pointers
:p.The :q.final boss:eq. of pointers is the difficult craft of 
:hp2.function pointers.:ehp2. These are pointers that, as the name 
implies, point to functions and allow you to call them. These are 
frequently used in a data structure called a :hp1.vtable:ehp1., but we 
will not be discussing those.
:i2.Function pointer
:p.Here is a sample of defining and using a function pointer:
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:xmp.
int add(int a, int b) {
    return a + b;
}
 
void demo() {
    int (*ptr)(int, int);         // leave off the arg names
    ptr = add;                    // set ptr to the address of add()
    int result1 = add(5, 10);
    int result2 = ptr(5, 10);
    int result3 = (*ptr)(5, 10);  // all three of these work!
}
:exmp.
:figcap.Function pointer example
:efig.
:p.As you can see, there are three valid ways of calling a function 
pointer.
:note.If you set a function pointer to an invalid address like some 
random memory address or to a variable, your microcontroller will crash!
:h2 id=casts.Casting
:p.A powerful feature found in C and almost always seen around pointers 
is the concept of a :hp2.cast.:ehp2. A cast permits you to transform 
the width of a variable (as in, the number of bytes that a variable 
takes up in memory) or its signage (signed or unsigned).
:p.Say that you declare a pointer of type :pk.void:epk. that points to 
some output buffer. Depending on the data type that you write to that 
pointer's memory location, different things may happen; let us assume 
that a simple character display controller watches the memory address 
:pv.0x001015A0:epv. and blasts text onto a screen. Here is a sample 
that implements a system like this:
:i1.Casting
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:xmp.
void* display = 0x001015A0;
 
void printString(char* text, int length) {
    for(int i = 0; i < length; i++) {
        *(char*)display = text&lbrk.i&rbrk.;
    }
}
 
void printInt(int value) {
    *(int*)display = value;
}
 
void demo() {
    char* message = "This is a test";
    printString(message, 14);
    int number = 5;
    printInt(number);
}
:exmp.
:figcap.Pointer casting example
:efig.
:p.As you can see, we started with a :pk.void:epk. pointer and 
converted it into either a :pk.char:epk. or :pk.int:epk. pointer based 
on which data type we wished to output.
:p.Something also very important (as discussed in :hdref refid=ptrmth.) 
is the understanding that if you change the type of a pointer pointing 
into an array to something else that :hp1.isn't:ehp1. the same as the 
original array definition type, you will be performing misaligned 
memory access and may get confused!
:h1 id=preproc.Preprocessor
:p.As you learned back at the start of this book, the 
:hp3.preprocessor:ehp3. is one of the stages/programs that is called 
when you compile your C program. The preprocessor uses various control 
statements to implement:
:ul.
:li.Macros
:li.Conditional compilation
:li.Custom errors and warnings
:li.Insertion of files
:fn.Primarily :hp2.headers.:ehp2. 
:efn.
:eul.
:p.The preprocessor statements always start with a pound (:pk.#:epk.) 
starting in the first column of the file. Let us examine some of these:
:h2.File Inclusion
:p.The most-commonly used function of the C preprocessor is 
the:pk.#include:epk. operator, which is used as follows:
:i1.include (preprocessor)
:xmp.#include <stm32l4xx.h>
:exmp.
:p.This will result in the contents of a file (at a specific location) 
named :pv.stm32l4xx.h:epv. being inserted into your program at the line 
the statement is on.
:p.:hp2.For a list of C headers you can use in your program,:ehp2. see 
:hdref refid=hdrs.!
:p.There are actually :hp1.two:ehp1. ways of specifying file paths:
:ol.
:li.If the filename is enclosed in :pk.< >:epk., the :hp5.system 
inclusion search path:ehp5. will be searched
:li.If the filename is enclosed in :pk." ":epk., the current directory
:fn.:q.Directory:eq. is an old term for what we call a 
:hp5.folder:ehp5. today, and is more frequently used in programming 
contexts!
:efn.
is searched
:eol.
:h3.Inclusion Search Path
:p.UNIX C compilers (including UNIX-style C compilers, which the GCC 
from STM32CubeIDE and ARM Clang from &mu.Vision are both considered) 
have a compiler argument that lets you specify a custom inclusion 
search path. Though you won't need to enter this on STM32CubeIDE 
projects (as the IDE will automatically find any files in 
the:pk.inc:epk. directories of your project and add those to the search 
path), the compiler is: :pk.-Idirname:epk.
:h2.Macros
:p.A :hp3.macro:ehp3. is a very useful feature of the C preprocessor 
that allows you to avoid the need for typing in tons and tons of code 
over and over; :hp5.a macro is a form of text substitution.:ehp5. 
:i1.define (preprocessor)
:p.Macros come in two varieties:
:ol.
:li.Text macros
:li.Macros with arguments
:eol.
:p.Let us examine text macros first. Say you have the following code:
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:xmp.
#define ANSWER 15
 
void doSomething() {
    if(input == ANSWER) {
        ...
    }
    ...
}
:exmp.
:figcap.Text macros example
:efig.
:p.This example shows a macro definition that will replace any 
occurrences of the text :pv.ANSWER:epv. in the program with 
:pv.15:epv., irrespective of context.
:h3.Macros With Arguments
:p.Sometimes, you may want to use a macro to replace a block of code -- 
for instance, if your program has lots of back-to-back :pk.else if:epk. 
statements with similar condition checks, it may make sense to use a 
macro that takes an argument.
:p.Examine the following sample code:
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:xmp.
#define CHECK(number) if(answer == number)
 
int decision(int answer) {
    CHECK(1) {
        return 12;
    }
    CHECK(2) {
        return 24;
    }
    return 0;          // fall-through if no cases match and leave
 
}
:exmp.
:figcap.Macro with argument example
:efig.
:p.This may seem rather confusing, so, let's expand the macro and see 
what the generated code that the compiler will actually end up 
compiling looks like:
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:xmp.
int decision(int answer) {
    if(answer == 1) {
        return 12;
    }
    if(answer == 2) {
        return 24;
    }
    return 0;          // fall-through if no cases match and leave
 
}
:exmp.
:figcap.Macro with argument example (expanded)
:efig.
:h3.Semicolon Consumption
:p.The C compiler will consume (i.e. skip past) as many semicolons as 
it can until the next statement is seen. A semicolon on its own, not 
associated with any code, is called a :hp2.null statement.:ehp2. Such a 
thing would look like this:
:i1.Null statement
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:xmp.
int doSomething() {
    return 1;;;;;;;;;;;
}
:exmp.
:figcap.Null statement example
:efig.
:p.Believe it or not, this is :hp1.completely:ehp1. valid! This can 
become useful when we wish to have a statement that might look cleaner 
as a macro, like this for example:
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:p.Un-expanded:
:xmp.
#define LEAVE(n) return n;
 
int doSomething() {
    LEAVE(5);
}
:exmp.
:p.Expanded:
:xmp.
int doSomething() {
    return 5;;
}
:exmp.
:figcap.Null statement example with macro
:efig.
:p.Note that double semicolon there in the macro-expanded version of 
the code.
:h3.Multiline Macros
:p.If you ever need to make a macro have multiple lines, you will need 
to use the :hp2.backslash:ehp2. key (:pk.\:epk.). Here is an example of 
a multiline macro:
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:xmp.
#define CHECK_LEAVE(target, value) \
    if(entry == target) {          \
        return value;              \
    }                              // no backslash here!
 
int lookupTable(int entry) {
    CHECK_LEAVE(5, 12);            // null statement!
    CHECK_LEAVE(8, 41);
    CHECK_LEAVE(10, 63);
}
:exmp.
:figcap.Multiline macro example
:efig.
:p.You will want to use the backslash on all lines :hp1.except for the 
last line.:ehp1.
:h3.Command-line definition
:p.You can also define macros on the C compiler command line with 
the:pk.-D:epk. argument, like so:
:xmp.cc -c myfile.c -DMYMACRO=1
:exmp.
:p.This defines the macro :pv.MYMACRO:epv. and sets its value to 1. You 
would want to use this to implement conditional compilation; look down 
the page a bit to learn about that.
:note.Please don't use command-line macro definition to define anything 
more sophisticated than simple variable substation macros!
:h3.Undefining Macros
:p.If for whatever reason you wish to :hp1.undefine:ehp1. a macro after 
it is defined, you can do this pretty easily:
:i1.undef (preprocessor)
:xmp.#undef MYMACRO
:exmp.
:h2.Conditional Compilation
:p.:hp2.Conditional compilation:ehp2. is a term that refers to having a 
program that compiles differently based on the presence of certain 
variables. In the case of C, we implement this by testing whether or 
not a macro is defined (or by testing the value of a macro).
:p.There are two groups of keywords that are used to implement 
conditional compilation:
:i1.ifdef (preprocessor)
:i1.ifndef (preprocessor)
:i1.else (preprocessor)
:i1.endif (preprocessor)
:i1.if (preprocessor)
:i1.elif (preprocessor)
:ol.
:li.Generation 1
:ul.
:li.:pk.#ifdef:epk.
:li.:pk.#ifndef:epk.
:li.:pk.#else:epk.
:li.:pk.#endif:epk. 
:eul.
:li.Generation 2
:ul.
:li.:pk.#if:epk.
:li.:pk.#elif:epk.
:li.:pk.#else:epk.
:li.:pk.#endif:epk. 
:eul.
:eol.
:p.As one might imagine by the :q.generations:eq. of keywords listed 
above, the Generation 2 keywords were not available in C compilers 
before 1989.
:fn.For those interested in the history of C, there were several C 
compilers popular from 1990-1995 that did not fully implement the C89 
version of the C preprocessor, resulting in programmers being unable to 
use the Generation 2 preprocessor conditional compilation keywords!
:efn.
:p.Let us examine the usage of both of these:
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:p.Generation 1
:xmp.
#define DEBUG 1                    // you would change this
 
#ifdef DEBUG                       // only a #define check
void debugger() {
    // do something special in the debug version
}
#else
void debugger() {}                 // do nothing otherwise
#endif
:exmp.
:p.Generation 2
:xmp.
#define DEBUG 2                    // you would change this
 
#if DEBUG == 1                     // compare the value instead
void debugger() {
    // debugging type 1
}
#elif DEBUG == 2
void debugger() {
    // debugging type 2
}
#else
void debugger() {}                 // no debugging code
#endif
:exmp.
:figcap.Conditional compilation examples
:efig.
:h2.Custom errors and warnings
:p.You can use the C preprocessor to write your own errors and warnings 
into your program, which is useful if you are using conditional 
compilation and the user has specified some kind of irreconcilable 
difference or unusable sequence of configuration parameters.
:p.There are two keywords that implement this feature:
:ol.
:li.:pk.#warning:epk.
:li.:pk.#error:epk. 
:eol.
:p.Take the following example, modified from one above:
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:xmp.
#define DEBUG 2
 
#if DEBUG == 1
void debugger() {
    // debugging type 1
}
#elif DEBUG == 2
#warning "debugging type 2 selected! performance will be slower!"
void debugger() {
    // debugging type 2
}
#else
#error "no debugging type specified! cannot compile!"
#endif
:exmp.
:figcap.Custom error/warning example
:efig.
:h1 id=ilasm.Inline Assembly
:p.C allows you to code assembler statements directly into your 
program, without having to also have assembly files (like you did in 
Computer Systems class) linked into your project.
:fn.If you do that, this means you have to figure out how to make an 
assembly function that is compatible with the C function calling 
convention!
:efn.
:p.There are two :q.flavors:eq. of inline assembly:
:h2.Basic Inline Assembly
:p.If you wish to include totally static inline assembler statements 
that don't reference any variables, you can do so like this:
:i1.asm function
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:xmp.
void enableInterrupts() {
    asm("cpsie i");
}
:exmp.
:figcap.Basic inline assembly example
:efig.
:p.The :pk.cpsie i:epk. instruction means :q.Change Processor State, 
Interrupt Enable (Interrupts On).:eq.
:p.If you encounter issues, you can add :pv.volatile:epv. keyword to 
the statement such that the statement now reads :pk.asm 
volatile("XXXX"):epk. 
:i2.volatile
:h2.Extended Inline Assembly
:p.If you wish to reference any variables, the compiler will allow you 
to substitute those into the assembler statements 
as:pk.%0:epk.,:pk.%1:epk., etc. In other words, if you plug in a 
variable name, you will reference it as :pk.%0:epk. in the 
statement.However, if you use the more complicated :hp5.custom-named 
variable approach:ehp5., you can use an actual variable name instead of 
a number!
:i2.Extended syntax (percents)
:p.Likewise, you will need to specify the following things:
:ol.
:li.All of your :hp2.input operands:ehp2.
:li.All of your :hp2.output operands:ehp2.
:li.Any registers that your assembler statement altered, in the 
:hp2.clobber list:ehp2. 
:eol.
:p.Now, there are two forms of extended inline assembler statements:
:ol.
:li.Positional variables (this is the aforementioned :pk.%0:epk. thing)
:li.Custom-named variables
:eol.
:p.No matter which you use, they both follow the same basic syntax:
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:xmp.
void magic() {
    asm volatile(
        "statement"
        : outputs
        : inputs
        : clobbers
    );
}
:exmp.
:figcap.Extended inline assembly syntax
:efig.
:h3.Positional Variables
:p.The key thing to remember using this syntax form is that the 
variables you reference will be dropped straight into the assembler 
statement with format-specifier-style substitutions!
:fn.A :q.format specifier:eq. is the format string that the 
:pv.printf:epv. and :pv.scanf:epv. family of C library statements use.
See :hdref refid=fstring. for more information! You probably won't need 
to use these though!!
:efn.
:p.Here is an example, then we will look at what happens and why:
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:xmp.
void storer(uint32_t* address, uint32_t value) {
    asm volatile(
        "str %1, &lbrk.%0&rbrk."
        :                             // outputs (none)
        : "r" value, "r" address      // inputs
        : "memory"                    // we modified memory
    );
}
:exmp.
:figcap.Extended inline assembly positional variables
:efig.
:p.Now, this statement has no outputs (since we aren't reading anything 
into any registers or memory addresses) and two inputs (the 
:pv.address:epv. and the :pv.value:epv.).
:p.The :pk."memory":epk. means that we are :hp3.modifying memory:ehp3. 
-- this function just simply stores a 32-bit variable at some memory 
address. If you are :hp3.modifying the condition code:ehp3. (which 
would occur if you use any math instructions), you would 
specify:pk."cc":epk. instead.
:p.You can also see the :q.constraint lists:eq. holding 
those:pk."=r":epk. terms. This tells the compiler to pick a register 
(or several) for your statement to use. You can get the compiler to 
allocate the following things for you:
:ul.
:li.:pk."=r":epk. is for a :hp2.register:ehp2.
:li.:pk."=w":epk. is for a :hp2.floating-point register:ehp2.
:li.:pk."=I":epk. places in an :hp2.integer constant:ehp2.
:li.:pk."=m":epk. is for a :hp2.memory address:ehp2. 
:fn.This is really for the Intel x86 or the IBM System Z instruction 
sets, where there is a specific way that you pass memory addresses
:efn.
 
:eul.
:lblbox.Register Naming
:p.Now, you might ask :hp1.:q.Evie, where in the world are the register 
names?!:eq.:ehp1. Well, you cannot just take any register and use it 
:hp1.because the compiler may be using that for a variable 
already!:ehp1. This is why you have to let the compiler figure out 
which registers you can use
:elblbox.
:h3.Custom-named Variables
:p.This syntax is a bit more advanced than the previous :q.simpler:eq. 
form of doing extended inline assembly. This one is as follows:
:p.Since this seems inconceivably difficult at first glance, let us 
examine a working example:
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:xmp.
uint32_t adder(uint32_t in1, uint32_t in2) {
    uint32_t answer;
 
    asm volatile(
        "add %&lbrk.out&rbrk., %&lbrk.a&rbrk.,  %&lbrk.b&rbrk."
        : &lbrk.out&rbrk. "=r" (answer)         // outputs
        : &lbrk.a&rbrk. "r" (in1),              // inputs
          &lbrk.b&rbrk. "r" (in2)
        : "cc"                        // modified the cond. code
    );
 
    return answer;
}
:exmp.
:figcap.Extended inline assembly custom-named variables
:efig.
:p.This statement is passingly similar to the basic syntax example, 
except this one has an output register (since we need to get our result 
from the statement somehow). As you can see in the square brackets, we 
substitute in the names we want.
:h1.Storage Classes and Qualifiers
:p.In your program, you may wish to override the so-called :hp2.storage 
class:ehp2. of a variable. The storage class defines how a variable 
will be stored and how it will be moved around a function. Likewise, 
you may wish to add a :hp2.qualifier:ehp2. if you want to lock a 
variable or prevent the C compiler from optimizing access to the 
variable.
:fn.One might ask why they could possibly want to un-optimize 
something, and the answer is simple: you will want to use 
the:pk.volatile:epk. keyword (which this chapter discusses shortly 
after where this footnote appears) whenever you are using variables 
within interrupt service routines.
:efn.
:h2 id=storcls.Storage Classes
:p.There are four storage classes you can stick before the type of your 
variable:
:i1.auto
:i1.register (storage class)
:i1.static
:i1.extern
:ol.
:li.:pk.auto:epk.
:p.This defines the variable such that it is automatically created and 
destroyed when you enter a function. For a global variable,
:fn.A global variable is a variable defined :hp1.outside:ehp1. a 
function.
:efn.
this keyword does nothing; for a local variable,
:fn.A local variable is a variable defined :hp1.inside:ehp1. a function.
:efn.
it is the normal way of defining a variable. :hp5.By default, this 
keyword is secretly present on every variable:ehp5. and you don't need 
to type it every time since it's the stock behavior for every variable.
:li.:pk.register:epk.
:p.This forces a variable to stay located within registers. This 
keyword may have been seen in performance-critical C code back in the 
1980s, but your STM32's ARM processor has lots of registers and the C 
compiler has to put every variable in a register anyways (because ARM 
is RISC).
:li.:pk.static:epk.
:p.If you define a variable as :pv.static:epv. within a function, its 
value will persist across several runs of a function; this is the 
opposite of the behavior that :pv.auto:epv. instills and is 
:hp5.not:ehp5. the default unless you ask for it.
:li.:pk.extern:epk.
:p.If you define a variable with :pv.extern:epv., you are telling the C 
compiler that the variable cannot be found within the current C source 
file and that it should let the linker resolve the variable's name into 
an address. You can create :pv.extern:epv. references to any global 
variable in your program.
:eol.
:h2 id=quals.Qualifiers
:p.You can put a qualifier before the storage class to restrict the 
behavior of variables to certain conditions:
:i1.const
:i1.volatile (qualifier)
:ol.
:li.:pk.const:epk.
:p.Make a variable constant/read-only.
:li.:pk.volatile:epk.
:p.Make any access to a variable non-optimized. This is recommended for 
any variables that you use in interrupt service routines or IRQ 
handlers.
:li.:pk.restrict:epk.
:p.This is used to mark a pointer as the sole way to access a variable, 
and the base variable name that the pointer points to will never be 
used to access it. This is useful when you are using pointers to access 
arrays, and it allows the compiler to employ useful optimization 
techniques (like vectorization).
:eol.
:h2.Keyword Position Summary
:p.The following diagram shows the layout of these newly-introduced 
keywords on a variable definition.
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:cgraphic.
&Ul.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Td.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Td.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Td.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Ur.
&Lv. qualifier &Lv.  sclass  &Lv.   type   &Lv.   name   &Lv.
&Ll.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tu.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tu.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tu.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lr.
:ecgraphic.
:figcap.Storage class/qualifier positioning
:efig.
:h1.C Keywords Reference
:p.Here is a series of useful tables that lists out the keywords we 
have learned about so far:
:h2.Flow Control
:p.These are your core keywords that control program execution.
:table cols='1i * 2i'.
:tcap.C Keywords: Flow Control
:thd.
:c.:hp2.Keyword:ehp2.
:c.:hp2.Description:ehp2.
:c.:hp2.Location:ehp2.
:ethd.
:row split=yes.
:c.:pk.break:epk.
:c.Exit from a :pv.while:epv., :pv.for:epv., or :pv.case:epv.
block
:c.:hdref refid=switch.
:row split=yes.
:c.:pk.case:epk.
:c.Start a region of code to run when the conditions on the
statement are met (within a :pv.switch:epv. statement)
:c.:hdref refid=switch.
:row split=yes.
:c.:pk.continue:epk.
:c.Jump to the next iteration of a :pv.while:epv. or
:pv.for:epv. loop immediately
:c.:hdref refid=while.
:row split=yes.
:c.:pk.default:epk.
:c.If no other :pv.case:epv. statements
match, this one will be ran (within a :pv.switch:epv.
statement)
:c.:hdref refid=switch.
:row split=yes.
:c.:pk.do:epk.
:c.Run a block of a :pv.while:epv. loop :hp1.before:ehp1. the
condition statement
:c.:hdref refid=dowhile.
:row split=yes.
:c.:pk.else:epk.
:c.Used in an :pv.if:epv. statement with or without some
:pv.else if:epv. statements to define conditions within the
:pv.if:epv. statement
:c.:hdref refid=elseif.
:row split=yes.
:c.:pk.if:epk.
:c.Run code if a condition is met
:c.:hdref refid=ifstmt.
:row split=yes.
:c.:pk.return:epk.
:c.Return a variable value when leaving a function body (only
for functions that return a type; :pv.void:epv. functions are
exempt from this)
:c.:hdref refid=return.
:row split=yes.
:c.:pk.switch:epk.
:c.Provide a simple way of evaluating multiple back-to-back
conditions in lieu of an :pv.if:epv. statement
:c.:hdref refid=switch.
:etable.
:h2.Type Keywords
:p.These keywords specify variable types; the :pk.stdint.h:epk. types 
are a superset of these. For those, see the table in 
