:h0.Programming the STM32
:p.Now that you understand the C language and its syntax/rules, we will 
now apply our knowledge and write some programs specifically for our 
STM32 board!
:h1.Basic STM32 Program Structure
:p.Before examining some of the tasks we can perform, let us first 
explore how we should start our program!
:note.This chapter will :hp5.not:ehp5. cover actually 
:hp1.creating:ehp1. projects -- if you need help with that, please see 
:hdref refid=mxproj.!
:h2 id=hdrs.Including the Headers
:p.The STM32 Development Toolchain (of which STM32CubeIDE provides for 
us) provides a number of important :hp3.headers:ehp3. we can use:
:i1.STM32 Headers
:table cols='1i *'.
:tcap.Base C Library Headers
:thd.
:c.:hp2.Header Name:ehp2.
:c.:hp2.Description:ehp2.
:ethd.
:row split=yes.
:c.:pk.float.h:epk.
:c.Floating-point type definitions
:row split=yes.
:c.:pk.limits.h:epk.
:c.Definitions for the largest numbers/maximums for each type
:row split=yes.
:c.:pk.math.h:epk.
:c.Various algebra and trig functions
:row split=yes.
:c.:pk.stdint.h:epk.
:c.C99 datatypes (:pv.uint322_t:epv. and others)
:row split=yes.
:c.:pk.string.h:epk.
:c.C string functions
:row split=yes.
:etable.
:table cols='1i *'.
:tcap.STM32 C Library Headers
:thd.
:c.:hp2.Header Name:ehp2.
:c.:hp2.Description:ehp2.
:ethd.
:row split=yes.
:c.:pk.stm32l4xx.h:epk.
:c.STM32L4xx (ELEC 3040/3050 board) definitions
:row split=yes.
:c.:pk.stm32f4xx.h:epk.
:c.STM32F4xx (ELEC 2220 board) definitions
:row split=yes.
:c.:pk.core_cm4.h:epk.
:c.Basic ARM Cortex-M4 components (automatically included)
:etable.
:h2.The Main Function
:p.Now that you know which headers you need to include,
:fn.Hint for 3040/3050: you want :pk.stm32l4xx.h:epk. at a minimum, and 
you likely want :pk.stdint.h:epk. too!
:efn.
let us look at the basic contents of a program.
:i1.main() function
:p.Here is the :q.minimum viable example:eq. you can use:
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:xmp.
#include <stm32l4xx.h>
#include <stdint.h>
 
int main() {
    // program goes here
}
:exmp.
:figcap.STM32 C program template (STM32L4xx board)
:efig.
:note.If you are using the Computer Systems board (perhaps you are 
reading this for a Capstone project), use the :pk.stm32f4xx.h:epk. 
header instead of :pk.stm32l4xx.h:epk.!
:h2.Program Startup Process
:p.While you certainly see that :pv.int main():epv. function, there are 
actually several other things that occur :hp1.before:ehp1. you enter 
your :pv.main:epv. function! Here they are:
:ol.
:li.The :pk.startup.h:epk. assembly-language program
:fn.This :pk.startup.h:epk. file is :hp5.always:ehp5. included with 
your program when you compile it!
:efn.
initializes core system peripherals.
:li.The :pv.int main():epv. function is called.
:li.If your program exits from the :pv.main:epv. function, there is an 
infinite loop in :pk.startup.s:epk. that the program will land in.
:eol.
:h2.Filling Out Your Program
:p.You will, naturally, want to include more than just a :pv.main:epv. 
function that'll exit instantly. Here is a slightly more complex 
example that shows function definition and more:
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:xmp.
#include <stm32l4xx.h>
#include <stdint.h>
 
void GPIOsetup() {
    ...
}
 
void interruptsetup() {
    ...
}
 
void counter() {
    ...
}
 
int main() {
    GPIOsetup();
    interruptsetup();
    while(1) {
        counter();
        __asm__("wfi");
    }
}
:exmp.
:figcap.More-complex STM32 C program
:efig.
:p.As you can see in the above example, I have an assembly-language 
statement in the program! This is wrapped in 
the:pk.__asm__("XXXX"):epk. compiler built-in function. For more 
information on this, flip back to :hdref refid=ilasm..
:h1.GPIO
:p.The first thing you will want to configure are the :hp2.general 
purpose input/output:ehp2. pins -- these let your STM32 easily talk to 
the outside world. The GPIO pins, as you learned in Computer Systems 
class, are grouped into 16-pin :hp5.ports:ehp5. wherein each pin can be 
configured independently (but you end up accessing the entire port 
register at the same time for each pin).
:i1.GPIOx registers
:h2 id=moder.Basic Pin Configuration
:p.The STM32 device header you included includes :pv.struct:epv. 
definitions for the various GPIO registers as well as helpful textual 
macros that alleviate the need to type in individual bits using binary 
literals. Some of the registers we will be using in this exercise are:
:i2.MODER
:ul.
:li.The :hp5.Register and Clock Control:ehp5. register, :pk.RCC:epk.
:ul.
:li.:pk.RCC->AHB2ENR:epk. 
:fn.This is the C statement you will type in to use this 
register;:pk.RCC:epk. is a structure pointer, so you use the arrow 
operator :pv.->:epv. to access the members.
:efn.
-- the AHB2 peripheral clock enable register
:eul.
:li.The :hp5.GPIO:ehp5. registers, :pk.GPIOx:epk.
:ul.
:li.:pk.GPIOx->MODER:epk. -- the mode register that configures pins as 
inputs, outputs, alternates, or analogs
:li.:pk.GPIOx->IDR:epk. -- the register that allows you to 
:hp5.read:ehp5. GPIO pins (inputs)
:li.:pk.GPIOx->ODR:epk. -- the register that allows you to 
:hp5.write:ehp5. GPIO pins (outputs)
:eul.
:eul.
:p.There are several more, and you can find more information about 
these in the books listed in :hdref refid=biblio..
:p.Now, in order to actually configure GPIO pins, you must first 
:hp2.enable the GPIO clock.:ehp2. 
:fn.You have to do this because by default on the STM32, all of the 
peripherals are powered-down and must be manually enabled using one of 
the :pk.RCC:epk. control registers.
:efn.
To do this, simply set the :pv.GPIOAEN:epv. bit of:pk.RCC->AHB2ENR:epk.:
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:xmp.
#include <stm32l4xx.h>
 
void gpiosetup() {
    RCC->AHB2ENR |= RCC_AHB2ENR_GPIOAEN;
    ...
}
 
int main() {
    gpiosetup();
    while(1) {
        __asm__("wfi");
    }
}
:exmp.
:figcap.GPIOA clock enablement
:efig.
:p.The :pv.stm32l4xx.h:epv. header has a macro that defines 
:pv.GPIOAEN:epv. as 1, which is the zeroth bit of the register (which 
corresponds to GPIOA's clock). Once the clock activates, we can 
configure the :hp2.mode register:ehp2. to set the behavior of each pin.
The :pk.GPIOA->MODER:epk. register is laid out as follows:
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:cgraphic.
&Ul.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Td.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh./&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Td.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Td.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Ur.
&Lv. Px15  &Lv. PxNN  &Lv.  Px1  &Lv.  Px0  &Lv.
&Tr.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Td.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Ju.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh./&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Ju.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Td.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Ju.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Td.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tl.
&Lv. A &Lv. B &Lv. ..... &Lv. A &Lv. B &Lv. A &Lv. B &Lv.
&Ll.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tu.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tu.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh./&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tu.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tu.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tu.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tu.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lr.
:ecgraphic.
:figcap.GPIOx_MODER layout
:efig.
:p.The :pk.AB:epk. bit pattern for each register controls the mode, 
which can be one of the following:
:table cols='1i 2i'.
:tcap.GPIO MODER Bit Patterns
:thd.
:c.:hp2.AB:ehp2.
:c.:hp2.Mode:ehp2.
:ethd.
:row split=yes.
:c.:pk.00:epk.
:c.Input
:row split=yes.
:c.:pk.01:epk.
:c.Output
:row split=yes.
:c.:pk.10:epk.
:c.Alternate Function
:row split=yes.
:c.:pk.11:epk.
:c.Analog Mode
:etable.
:p.Given this information, say we want to enable :pk.PB3:epk. as output.
:fn.:pk.PB3:epk. corresponds to a green LED at the bottom-right of your 
Nucleo-L432 board!
:efn.
:note.You have to :hp5.clear the interesting bits beforehand:ehp5. 
using :pk.&=:epk., then set them to what you want with :pk.|=:epk. 
afterwards!
:p.The following code will configure PB3 as output:
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:xmp.
#include <stm32l4xx.h>
 
void gpiosetup() {
    RCC->AHB2ENR |= RCC_AHB2ENR_GPIOBEN;   // note: GPIOB
    //   GPIOB pins:  3.2.1.0.
    GPIOB->MODER &= &tilde.0b11000000;           // clear bits
    GPIOB->MODER |=  0b01000000;
}
 
int main() {
    gpiosetup();
    while(1) {
        __asm__("wfi");
    }
}
:exmp.
:figcap.PB3 output enablement example
:efig.
:lblbox.Clearing and Setting
:p.To clear bits, use this:
:xmp.GPIOA->MODER &= &tilde.0b11000000;
:exmp.
:p.To set bits, use this:
:xmp.GPIOA->MODER |= 0b11000000;
:exmp.
:note.You have to use the binary complement (i.e. NOT) operator to 
:hp1.invert:ehp1. to values for clearing, or you will do the reverse of 
what you wanted to!
:elblbox.
:h3.Outputting Values
:p.Now, at this point, you will inevitably want to actually write some 
data to the output. Here is a handy list containing code chunks for 
:hp2.setting:ehp2. and :hp2.clearing:ehp2. output pins:
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:p.To set (enable) PB3:
:xmp.
//              3210
GPIOB->ODR |= 0b1000;
:exmp.
:p.To clear (disable) PB3:
:xmp.
//               3210
GPIOB->ODR &= &tilde.0b1000;
:exmp.
:figcap.Setting and clearing PB3 example
:efig.
:h2.Configuring and Using Inputs
:p.First, flip back to :hdref refid=moder. and make sure you pay close 
attention to the :pv.MODER:epv. value to declare a pin as 
input::pk.00:epk.. Of course, you would use the :pv.&=:epv. operation 
to clear those bits. If you forget what this means, go back to 
:hdref refid=bitwise.!
:p.Here is an example that declares PA0 as an input:
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:xmp.
#include <stm32l4xx.h>
 
void gpiosetup() {
    RCC->AHB2ENR |= RCC_AHB2ENR_GPIOAEN;   // note: GPIOB
    //   GPIOB pins:   0.
    GPIOB->MODER &= &tilde.0b00;
}
 
int main() {
    gpiosetup();
    while(1) {
        __asm__("wfi");
    }
}
:exmp.
:figcap.PA0 input enablement example
:efig.
:p.In order to actually use these, you can read the :pk.IDR:epk. 
register like so:
:i1.Masking off (bits)
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:xmp.
if(GPIOA->IDR & 0b1 == 1) {
    // this pin is active
}
else {
    // this pin is not active
}
:exmp.
:figcap.PA0 input reading example
:efig.
:p.Now, you might be asking :q.Evie, why are you ANDing the IDR value 
with 1?:eq. Well, you want to :hp5.mask off:ehp5. bits such that you 
only :hp1.get what you want:ehp1. 
:lblbox.Special Pins on GPIOA
:p.:hp2.PA14:ehp2. and :hp2.PA15:ehp2. are special, declared as inputs 
by default, and are used to allow the debugger to communicate with the 
:hp5.ST-LINK:ehp5. chip on the underside of the board (this is the chip 
that drives the USB port). Because one of these is a clock and the 
other one is a data pin, their values jitter erratically and rapidly, 
so you must :hp1.mask off:ehp1. the values you want when you read from 
GPIOA!
:elblbox.
:h3 id=pupd.Pull-Up and Pull-Down Resistors
:p.Sometimes, you may wish to use a button that is just 
:hp1.floating:ehp1. 
:fn.This means that the button connects only to voltage or ground, 
rather than being a bi-state button that alternates between connecting 
its output pin to voltage or ground depending on whether or not the 
button is pressed. Basically every button ever made if a floating 
button!
:efn.
with your STM32. To do this and have it work properly, you have to 
employ :hp2.pull-up:ehp2. or :hp2.pull-down:ehp2. resistors or the 
button's value will seem to randomly jitter between on and off!
:fn.This is because static electricity can build up on the 
:hp1.gate:ehp1. of the MOSFETs comprising the :pv.IDR:epv. register, 
causing it to twiddle between 0 and 1.
:efn.
Here's a simple way to know when to use each:
:ul.
:li.If your button is connected to :hp2.ground:ehp2., you will use a 
:hp2.pull-up resistor:ehp2. and watch for when the :pv.IDR:epv. value 
for the pin goes to :pk.0:epk..
:li.If your button is connected to :hp2.voltage:ehp2., you will use a 
:hp2.pull-down resistor:ehp2. and watch for when the :pv.IDR:epv. value 
for the pin goes to :pk.1:epk..
:eul.
:note.It should be clear by now that the pull-up and pull-down 
resistors are :hp2.tiny resistors inside the STM32 package:ehp2. and 
not physical resistors that you have to place anywhere on your 
breadboard!
:note.You can only use pull-up or pull-down resistors when a pin is in 
:hp5.input:ehp5. mode. :hp2.Pull-up and pull-down resistors do nothing 
in output mode!:ehp2.
:p.The following figure shows you how the inside of the STM32 is laid 
out and how those PU/PD resistors are placed and connected:
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:cgraphic.
                  Vcc
                  &Lh.&Td.&Lh.
                   &Lv.
                  &Ul.&Tu.&Ur.
                  &Lv.P&Lv.
                  &Lv.U&Lv.
                  &Ll.&Td.&Lr.
                   &Lv.
                   &Lv.
&Ul.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Ur.        &Lv.       &Ul.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Ur.
&Lv. IDR bit &Tr.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Ju.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tl. Physical pin &Tr.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Ar.
&Ll.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lr.        &Lv.       &Ll.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lr.
                   &Lv.
                   &Lv.
                  &Ul.&Tu.&Ur.
                  &Lv.P&Lv.
                  &Lv.D&Lv.
                  &Ll.&Td.&Lr.
                   &Lv.
                  &Lh.&Tu.&Lh.
                  Gnd
:ecgraphic.
:figcap.STM32 pull-up/pull-down resistor wiring diagram
:efig.
:p.If you recall from :hdref refid=moder., you'll know the general 
:q.two-bits:eq. form of the register. The register we configure to use 
these resistors is :pk.GPIOx->PUPDR:epk..
:fn.:pk.PUPDR:epk. = Pull-Up/Down Register
:efn.
Here is a layout of the register's bits:
:i2.PUPDR
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:cgraphic.
&Ul.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Td.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh./&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Td.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Td.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Ur.
&Lv. Px15  &Lv. PxNN  &Lv.  Px1  &Lv.  Px0  &Lv.
&Tr.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Td.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Ju.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh./&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Ju.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Td.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Ju.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Td.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tl.
&Lv. D &Lv. U &Lv. ..... &Lv. D &Lv. U &Lv. D &Lv. U &Lv.
&Ll.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tu.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tu.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh./&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tu.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tu.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tu.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tu.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lr.
:ecgraphic.
:figcap.GPIOx_PUPDR layout
:efig.
:p.Given the :pk.D/U:epk. pattern, the following bit patterns are 
possible here:
:table cols='1i 2i'.
:tcap.GPIO PUPDR Bit Patterns
:thd.
:c.:hp2.UD:ehp2.
:c.:hp2.Mode:ehp2.
:ethd.
:row split=yes.
:c.:pk.00:epk.
:c.Neither pull-up nor pull-down
:row split=yes.
:c.:pk.01:epk.
:c.Pull-up
:row split=yes.
:c.:pk.10:epk.
:c.Pull-down
:row split=yes.
:c.:pk.11:epk.
:c.Both (impossible state, do not use!)
:etable.
:p.To actually use these, you can write something like this:
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:xmp.
#include <stm32l4xx.h>
 
void pupdsetup() {
    //   GPIOA pins:  1.0.
    GPIOA->MODER |= 0b1001; // PA0 = PU, PA1 = PD
}
 
void gpiosetup() {
    ...
}
 
int main() {
    gpiosetup();
    pupdsetup();
    while(1) {
        __asm__("wfi");
    }
}
:exmp.
:figcap.PA0 and PA1 pull-up and pull-down example
:efig.
:p.Now, use the pins as inputs!
:lblbox.Pull-up Voltage Leakage
:p.Did you know that you can actually somewhat use the pull-up and 
pull-down resistors as a way of tricking a pin declared as input to 
provide outputs?
:p.You can engage the pull-up to output a logic 1, and engage the 
pull-down to output a logic 0.
If you use this technique, make sure you have one or the other, but not 
both or neither, to prevent floating pins!
:p.This may sound like useless information, but using the pull-up 
resistors as outputs becomes very important if you need to drive a 
:hp1.keypad:ehp1. or any such similar device!
:elblbox.
:h2 id=altfnc.Alternate Function Mode
:p.Sometimes, you may wish to use all sorts of :q.fancy:eq. peripherals 
like:
:i2.AF/AFR
:ul.
:li.Serial ports:
:ul.
:li.UART (i.e. :q.asynchronous serial:eq.)
:li.SPI
:fn.Serial Peripheral Interface is :hp5.heavily:ehp5. used to drive SD 
cards, external sensors, serial RAM and ROM chips, debuggers from other 
manufacturers besides ST, and things like that!
:efn.
:li.I&sup2.C
:li.CAN
:fn.Controller Area Network is the serial bus often used in cars.
:efn.
:eul.
:li.Timers to generate PWM (see :hdref refid=pwm.)
:li.USB
:eul.
:p.You need to engage :hp2.alternate function:ehp2. mode to set these 
up. This requires you to do :hp1.two:ehp1. things:
:ol.
:li.Find the bits in :pk.GPIOx->MODER:epk. and set them to :pk.10:epk. 
like we covered in :hdref refid=moder.
:li.Use the :hp1.correct:ehp1. :pk.GPIOx->AFR&lbrk.y&rbrk.:epk. to 
select which alternate function you want for the pins you selected in 
the mode register
:eol.
:p.The :pk.AFR:epk. register is very strange, because each I/O pin can 
have up to :hp3.16:ehp3. alternate functions!
If you recall from Digital Logic Circuits class, you'll know that in 
order to count to 16 in binary (so, 0 to 15), you'll need :hp5.3:ehp5. 
bits. That means that the :pk.AFR:epk. register is :hp1.wider:ehp1. 
than :pk.MODER:epk., which will result in it being broken into multiple 
chunks as an :hp5.array.:ehp5.
:note.I say that each pin can be bound to one of 15 different alternate 
functions, but the STM32L4 and STM32F4 series boards that you will 
frequently encounter only provide :hp3.8:ehp3. alternate functions 
(that is, AF0 through AF7).
:p.Now, because there are 4 bits per pin, that means there are 
:hp1.two:ehp1. AFRs. The STM32 manuals refer to those as 
:pv.GPIOx_AFRL:epv. and :pv.GPIOx_AFRH:epv., but this isn't what you'll 
refer to them as in your C program; here is a handy table that explains 
the mapping:
:table cols='* * *'.
:tcap.GPIO AFRL/ARFH Mapping
:thd.
:c.:hp2.Bits:ehp2.
:c.:hp2.STM32 Manual Name:ehp2.
:c.:hp2.C Program Name:ehp2.
:ethd.
:row split=yes.
:c.Px0 through Px7
:c.:pv.GPIOx_AFRL:epv.
:c.:pk.GPIOx->AFR&lbrk.0&rbrk.:epk.
:row split=yes.
:c.Px8 through Px15
:c.:pv.GPIOx_AFRH:epv.
:c.:pk.GPIOx->AFR&lbrk.1&rbrk.:epk.
:etable.
:p.So, as you can see, it's split in two in the middle and is accessed 
like an array. Now, let us examine the layout of those two registers:
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:cgraphic.
GPIOx_AFRL:
&Ul.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Td.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh./&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Td.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Ur.
&Lv.      Px7      &Lv.         &Lv.      Px0      &Lv.
&Tr.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Td.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Td.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Td.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Ju.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh./&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Ju.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Td.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Td.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Td.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tl.
&Lv. D &Lv. C &Lv. B &Lv. A &Lv.         &Lv. D &Lv. C &Lv. B &Lv. A &Lv.
&Ll.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tu.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tu.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tu.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tu.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh./&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tu.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tu.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tu.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tu.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lr.
31                                        0
 
GPIOx_AFRH:
&Ul.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Td.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh./&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Td.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Ur.
&Lv.      Px15     &Lv.         &Lv.      Px8      &Lv.
&Tr.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Td.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Td.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Td.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Ju.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh./&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Ju.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Td.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Td.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Td.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tl.
&Lv. D &Lv. C &Lv. B &Lv. A &Lv.         &Lv. D &Lv. C &Lv. B &Lv. A &Lv.
&Ll.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tu.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tu.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tu.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tu.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh./&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tu.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tu.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tu.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tu.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lr.
31                                        0
:ecgraphic.
:figcap.GPIOx_AFRL and AFRH layout
:efig.
:p.The :pv.DCBA:epv. pattern is a :hp5.4-bit binary number:ehp5., so, 
if you want to select alternate function 3, you would set :pv.DCBA:epv. 
to :pv.0011:epv..
:note.In order to figure out :hp5.what the AF mappings are for each 
pin:ehp5., you will need to check the corresponding :hp1.device 
datasheet:ehp1.; see :hdref refid=biblio. for more information.
:p.Now, let us examine an example program that engages AF7 on PA9 and 
AF7 on PA10.
:fn.This enables the :pv.USART1:epv. interface; PA9 is transmit, and 
PA10 is receive. Using serial ports may be useful in your Capstone 
project!
:efn.
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:xmp.
// set PA9 and PA10 as AF; clear the interested bits first
GPIOA->MODER &= &tilde.0b1111000000000000000000;
GPIOA->MODER |=  0b101000000000000000000000;
// AFR bits:        10..9...8...
GPIOA->AFR&lbrk.1&rbrk. &= &tilde.0b111111110000;
GPIOA->AFR&lbrk.1&rbrk. |=  0b011101110000;
:exmp.
:figcap.PA9 and PA10 alternate function definition example
:efig.
:p.Now, what you end up doing with this alternate function is up to 
you! You will certainly use PWM in one of the lab assignments, so check 
:hdref refid=pwm. for more information on that.
:h2 id=analog.Analog Mode
:h1.Interrupts
:p.One of the most useful things you will ever encounter in the world 
of computing is that of the :hp2.interrupt.:ehp2. The purpose of an 
interrupt is to :hp1.temporarily stop the execution of a program, jump 
to a certain function, run some code, and return back to where you left 
off:ehp1. when :hp1.an input event or software trigger occurs.:ehp1.
:p.In the world of embedded systems, an :q.input event:eq. can be a 
button press, timer counter limit hit, data coming in over a serial 
interface, or a system interval timer; a :q.software trigger:eq. only 
really occurs when you are running a real operating system.
:fn.For those curious and for those who did not pay much attention in 
Operating Systems class, a :hp5.system call:ehp5. is implemented using 
an interrupt that your user programs :q.simulate:eq. using some kind of 
CPU instruction.
:efn.
:p.This section will cover interrupts as they relate to push buttons 
and other such momentary inputs; we will not be debouncing the button 
or anything with this code!
:p.Let us connect a push button to PA1. We will connect it like this:
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:p.Using the WaveForms board:
:cgraphic.
BTN1 &Al.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Ar. PA1
:ecgraphic.
:p.Using a real button:
:cgraphic.
VCC
&Lh.&Td.&Lh.
 &Lv.
 &Lv.
 &Lv.        &Lv.
 &Lv.      &Lh.&Lh.&Tu.&Lh.&Lh.
 &Lv.      &Au.   &Au.
 &Ll.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lr.   &Ll.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Ar. PA1
:ecgraphic.
:figcap.Button on PA1
:efig.
:note.If you are following this section to configure interrupts for 
your lab assignment(s), you will want to use the :hp1.first:ehp1. 
circuit wherein you use the :pk.BTN1:epk. output of the WaveForms board 
and wire it straight into PA1 on your STM32.
:p.:warning.Make sure all of the voltage switches on your WaveForms 
board are up; these are located at the top right of the white portion 
of the breadboard, the part that you take out of the board and take 
home after every lab!:ewarning.
:p.Now that you've decided that you want to use PA1, you need to do the 
following things to actually enable and use the interrupt:
:ol.
:li.Configure the GPIO pin that the button is wired to (PA1) as an 
input.
:li.If you are using a real button, enable the :hp1.pull-down 
resistor:ehp1. on PA1.
:fn.See :hdref refid=pupd. for help with this!
:efn.
:li.Determine which EXTI interrupt line you need to enable in the NVIC.
:li.Set the flags for the EXTI line (:pk.FTSR1:epk., :pk.PR1:epk., 
and:pk.IMR1:epk.) for a falling-edge-triggered interrupt.
:li.Enable the EXTI IRQ in the NVIC.
:li.Write an IRQ handler function.
:eol.
:h2.Understanding the NVIC
:p.Before we proceed, it is very helpful to know how exactly the 
:hp2.NVIC:ehp2. 
:fn.Nested Vectored Interrupt Controller
:efn.
works for the EXTI interrupts. See the following diagram for an example 
of how each GPIO pin results in an EXTI interrupt being generated:
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:artwork name=nvicexti.
:figcap.NVIC EXTI flow
:efig.
:p.As you can see, all of the GPIO pins numbered 0 can result in the 
production of the :pv.EXTI0:epv. interrupt. This means that PC3 would 
result in the production of the :pv.EXTI3:epv. interrupt, and PA1 will 
result in the production of :pv.EXTI1:epv..
:p.It should be noted that there are :hp1.many:ehp1. other interrupts 
the NVIC provides:
:ul.
:li.Core CPU interrupts: faults, system service call (SVC), the SysTick 
timer, non-maskable interrupt (NMI)
:li.External interrupts (EXTI)
:li.DMA completion interrupts
:li.Timers (see :hdref refid=timers.)
:li.Serial interface controllers: SPI, I&sup2.C, CAN, USB
:li.ADC completion interrupts (see :hdref refid=adc.)
:li.DAC completion interrupts
:eul.
:p.In this chapter, we are only looking at the EXTI interrupts!
:h2.Configuring Input Interrupts 
:p.Now that you understand the NVIC, let us proceed!
:h3.Configuring the EXTICR Register
:p.Before we can configure the interrupt properties of PA1, we must 
first enable it in the :pk.SYSCFG->EXTICR:epk. register. This, much in 
the same way the :pk.GPIOx->AFR:epk. register, is split into two. Just 
like the :pv.AFR:epv. register, each entry comprises :hp2.4:ehp2. bits 
(but only :hp2.3:ehp2. of which are actually used). There are a total 
of :hp2.4:ehp2. :pv.EXTICR:epv. registers, laid out as follows:
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:cgraphic.
SYSCFG_EXTICR1:
&Ul.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Td.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh./&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Td.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Ur.
&Lv.      Px7      &Lv.         &Lv.      Px0      &Lv.
&Tr.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Td.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Td.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Td.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Ju.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh./&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Ju.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Td.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Td.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Td.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tl.
&Lv. x &Lv. C &Lv. B &Lv. A &Lv.         &Lv. x &Lv. C &Lv. B &Lv. A &Lv.
&Ll.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tu.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tu.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tu.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tu.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh./&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tu.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tu.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tu.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tu.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lr.
15                   .                    0
                     .
                     .
 
SYSCFG_EXTICR4:
&Ul.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Td.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh./&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Td.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Ur.
&Lv.      Px15     &Lv.         &Lv.      Px8      &Lv.
&Tr.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Td.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Td.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Td.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Ju.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh./&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Ju.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Td.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Td.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Td.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tl.
&Lv. D &Lv. C &Lv. B &Lv. A &Lv.         &Lv. D &Lv. C &Lv. B &Lv. A &Lv.
&Ll.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tu.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tu.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tu.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tu.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh./&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tu.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tu.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tu.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tu.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lr.
15                                        0
:ecgraphic.
:figcap.SYSCFG_EXTICRx register layout
:efig.
:note.Only bits 0 to 15 are used in these registers, and the :pk.x:epk. 
means the bit is :q.dead:eq. and does not do anything!
:p.Here is a handy table that maps the four registers to their STM32 
manual name and C program variable name:
:table cols='* * *'.
:tcap.EXTICRx Mapping
:thd.
:c.:hp2.EXTI:ehp2.
:c.:hp2.STM32 Manual Name:ehp2.
:c.:hp2.C Program Name:ehp2.
:ethd.
:row split=yes.
:c.0 through 3
:c.:pv.SYSCFG_EXTICR1:epv.
:c.:pk.SYSCFG-&gtsym.EXTICR&lbrk.0&rbrk.:epk.
:row split=yes.
:c.4 through 7
:c.:pv.SYSCFG_EXTICR2:epv.
:c.:pk.SYSCFG-&gtsym.EXTICR&lbrk.1&rbrk.:epk.
:row split=yes.
:c.8 through 11
:c.:pv.SYSCFG_EXTICR3:epv.
:c.:pk.SYSCFG-&gtsym.EXTICR&lbrk.2&rbrk.:epk.
:row split=yes.
:c.12 through 15
:c.:pv.SYSCFG_EXTICR4:epv.
:c.:pk.SYSCFG-&gtsym.EXTICR&lbrk.3&rbrk.:epk.
:etable.
:p.So, there are two ways to populate the bits of the :pv.EXTICR:epv. 
register you need to write to (which, for our PA1 interrupt, is 
:pk.SYSCFG->EXTICR0｡:epk.):
:ol.
:li.By directly writing the bits
:li.Using the macro bitmask names
:fn.These are defined in :pv.stm32l4xx.h:epv.; you can right-click any 
of these terms after typing them in STM32CubeIDE and click the :q.Go to 
Definition:eq. button to see what these resolve to (with binary 
immediate or bit-shift patterns).
:efn.
 
:eol.
:p.Here is a sample of both:
:i1.EXTICR
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:xmp.
// using macro bitfield names; clearing first, then selecting PA
SYSCFG->EXTICR&lbrk.0&rbrk. &= &tilde.SYSCFG_EXTICR1_EXTI1;
SYSCFG->EXTICR&lbrk.0&rbrk. |= SYSCFG_EXTICR1_EXTI1_PA;
// using bits directly:
SYSCFG->EXTICR&lbrk.0&rbrk. &= &tilde.0b01110000;
SYSCFG->EXTICR&lbrk.0&rbrk. |= 0b00010000;
:exmp.
:figcap.EXTICR PA1 selection example
:efig.
:note.Make sure PA1 has been declared as an input :hp1.before:ehp1. 
proceeding (see :hdref refid=moder. for a refresher on this).
:h3.Setting the Interrupt Flags
:p.At this point, the NVIC has :q.routed:eq. the line from PA1, but we 
have not yet selected a rising-edge or falling-edge interrupt; 
likewise, we have not connected the EXTI block to the NVIC -- we have 
also not cleared the Pending Interrupt Flag that will raise the moment 
the interrupt is enabled. We will connect it after this.
:p.There are a number of registers in the :pk.EXTI:epk. struct that we 
are interested in: 
:i1.EXTI 
:i2.FTSR/RTSR 
:i2.PIF 
:i2.IMR/EMR
:table cols='1i *'.
:thd.
:c.:hp2.Register:ehp2.
:c.:hp2.Description:ehp2.
:ethd.
:row split=yes.
:c.:pk.EXTI->IMR1:epk.
:c.:hp1.Interrupt Mask Register,:ehp1. which connects and
disconnects the GPIO pin to the NVIC line
:row split=yes.
:c.:pk.EXTI->EMR1:epk.
:c.:hp1.Event Mask Register,:ehp1. which completely disables
event and interrupt generation (by default, every event is
:hp5.enabled:ehp5.)
:row split=yes.
:c.:pk.EXTI->RTSR1:epk.
:c.:hp1.Rising Trigger Selection Register,:ehp1. which enables
rising-edge interrupts for each GPIO line
:row split=yes.
:c.:pk.EXTI->FTSR1:epk.
:c.:hp1.Falling Trigger Selection Register,:ehp1. which enables
falling-edge interrupts for each GPIO line
:row split=yes.
:c.:pk.EXTI->SWIER1:epk.
:c.:hp1.Software Interrupt Event Register,:ehp1. wherein writing
a bit to the correct slot will result in the generation of an
interrupt by your program
:row split=yes.
:c.:pk.EXTI->PR1:epk.
:c.:hp1.Pending Register,:ehp1. wherein writing a 1 to the correct
slot :q.dismisses:eq. an interrupt (you will need to do this in your
IRQ handler function)
:etable.
:note.Just like there is an :pk.FTSR1:epk., there is also 
an:pk.FTSR2:epk. for additional interrupts -- you won't be using this, 
though!
:p.These registers are laid out as follows:
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:cgraphic.
EXTI_RTSR1:
&Ul.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Td.&Lh./&Lh.&Td.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Td.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Td.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Td.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Ur.
&Lv. 31| / &Lv. 3 | 2 | 1 | 0 &Lv. Interrupt Number
&Tr.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Ju.&Lh./&Lh.&Ju.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Ju.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Ju.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Ju.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tl.
&Lv. E &Lv. / &Lv. E &Lv. E &Lv. E &Lv. E &Lv.
&Ll.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tu.&Lh./&Lh.&Tu.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tu.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tu.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tu.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lr.
31                      0
 
EXTI_FTSR1:
&Ul.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Td.&Lh./&Lh.&Td.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Td.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Td.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Td.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Ur.
&Lv. 31| / &Lv. 3 | 2 | 1 | 0 &Lv.
&Tr.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Ju.&Lh./&Lh.&Ju.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Ju.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Ju.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Ju.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tl.
&Lv. E &Lv. / &Lv. E &Lv. E &Lv. E &Lv. E &Lv.
&Ll.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tu.&Lh./&Lh.&Tu.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tu.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tu.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tu.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lr.
31                      0
 
EXTI_IMR1:  
&Ul.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Td.&Lh./&Lh.&Td.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Td.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Td.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Td.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Ur.
&Lv. 31| / &Lv. 3 | 2 | 1 | 0 &Lv.
&Tr.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Ju.&Lh./&Lh.&Ju.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Ju.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Ju.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Ju.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tl.
&Lv. E &Lv. / &Lv. E &Lv. E &Lv. E &Lv. E &Lv.
&Ll.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tu.&Lh./&Lh.&Tu.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tu.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tu.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tu.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lr.
31                      0
 
EXTI_PR1:   
&Ul.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Td.&Lh./&Lh.&Td.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Td.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Td.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Td.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Ur.
&Lv. 31| / &Lv. 3 | 2 | 1 | 0 &Lv.
&Tr.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Ju.&Lh./&Lh.&Ju.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Ju.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Ju.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Ju.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tl.
&Lv. E &Lv. / &Lv. E &Lv. E &Lv. E &Lv. E &Lv.
&Ll.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tu.&Lh./&Lh.&Tu.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tu.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tu.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Tu.&Lh.&Lh.&Lh.&Lr.
31                      0
 
:ecgraphic.
:figcap.EXTI register layouts
:efig.
:p.So, if we want a :hp1.falling-edge interrupt,:ehp1. you will need to 
alter :pk.EXTI->FTSR1:epk., :pk.EXTI->PR1:epk., and :pk.EXTI->IMR1:epk.
:p.Here is some code that will do that:
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:xmp.
EXTI->FTSR1 |= EXTI_FTSR1_FT1;
EXTI->PR1 |= EXTI_PR1_PIF1;
EXTI->IMR1 |= EXTI_IMR1_IM1;
:exmp.
:figcap.PA1 interrupt flags configuration example
:efig.
:p.For PA5, you would replace the last number before the semicolon with 
5, so, :pk.EXTI_FTSR1_FT5:epk.. 
:h3.Enabling the Interrupt in the NVIC 
:p.Next, you need to use two macro-functions
:fn.These are functions defined with the :pk.inline:epk. keyword; you 
can learn about that by reading :hdref refid=inline..
:efn.
to tell the NVIC to unblock the path from the EXTI block to the NVIC 
block: 
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:xmp.
NVIC_ClearPendingIRQ(EXTI1_IRQn);
NVIC_EnableIRQ(EXTI1_IRQn);
:exmp.
 
:figcap.NVIC interrupt enablement example
:efig.
:p.This part is fairly simple! Note that the syntax of this really does 
say :pk.EXTI1_IRQn:epk.; you can see the :pk.1:epk. there is the 
variable part, so if you were using an interrupt on PB6, you would use 
:pk.EXTI6_IRQn:epk.. Before the program can run, though, you must run 
one more function to enable :hp1.all:ehp1. interrupts on the CPU 
globally:  
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:p.Using the C function:
:xmp.__enable_irq();
:exmp.
:p.Using inline assembly: 
:xmp.__asm__("cpsie i");
:exmp.
 
:figcap.Global interrupt enablement
:efig.
:note.There are :hp3.two underscores:ehp3. on both of those! 
:h3.Writing the ISR 
:p.Now that the interrupt can (in theory) fire, you need to write a 
function that the CPU will jump to. This is our :hp2.interrupt service 
routine:ehp2., or ISR for short. These have a :hp5.specific:ehp5. name 
that you cannot deviate from (see the info-box after the code sample 
for an explanation as to why this is the case)! 
:i1.ISR
:p.Since we are using :pv.EXTI1:epv. because we want PA1 to be our 
interrupt pin, we have to write a function named 
:pk.EXTI1_IRQHandler:epk. and it will have a :pv.void:epv. return type. 
:p.Here is the general form of an EXTI ISR: 
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:xmp.
#include <stm32l4xx.h> 
void gpiosetup() { 
     
void EXTI1_IRQHandler() {
    NVIC_ClearPendingIRQ(EXTI1_IRQn); // flush pending interrupts 
    // do something here with your button... 
    EXTI->PR1 |= EXTI_PR1_PIF1;       // we have processed the IRQ
} 
:exmp.
 
:figcap.EXTI IRQ handler function example
:efig.
:p.At this point, you're done! After the info-box, I will provide you 
with a complete code sample for more than one interrupt in case you 
think you forgot something. 
:lblbox.How are the IRQ Handler Functions Accessed? 
:p.In your :pk.startup.s:epk. file (provided by the STM32Cube 
development toolchain), there is a :hp1.function vtable:ehp1. 
consisting of an array of function pointers (see :hdref refid=fnptr.) 
stored at a very specific memory address. 
:p.When the EXTI1 interrupt comes in, the CPU will convert that into a 
numeric index to that function pointer array, extract that memory 
address, and then jump into that function (after saving the return 
address it needs to get back to what it was doing beforehand).  
:elblbox.
:h3.Summary and Complete Example 
:p.This enables PA1 and PA2 as interrupts. 
:fig width=column place=inline frame=rules.
:xmp keep=5.
#include <stm32l4xx.h> 
 
void gpiosetup() {
    RCC->AHB2ENR |= RCC_AHB2ENR_GPIOAEN;
    GPIOA->MODER &= &tilde.0b1111; // clear for input
}
 
void intsetup() { 
    // EXTICR input selection
    SYSCFG->EXTICR&lbrk.0&rbrk. &= &tilde.SYSCFG_EXTICR1_EXTI1;
    SYSCFG->EXTICR&lbrk.0&rbrk. |= SYSCFG_EXTICR1_EXTI1_PA;
    SYSCFG->EXTICR&lbrk.0&rbrk. &= &tilde.SYSCFG_EXTICR1_EXTI2;
    SYSCFG->EXTICR&lbrk.0&rbrk. |= SYSCFG_EXTICR1_EXTI2_PA;
    // flag configuration
    EXTI->FTSR1 |= EXTI_FTSR1_FT1;
    EXTI->PR1 |= EXTI_PR1_PIF1;
    EXTI->IMR1 |= EXTI_IMR1_IM1;
    EXTI->FTSR1 |= EXTI_FTSR1_FT2;
    EXTI->PR1 |= EXTI_PR1_PIF2;
    EXTI->IMR1 |= EXTI_IMR1_IM2;
    // NVIC enablement
    NVIC_ClearPendingIRQ(EXTI1_IRQn);
    NVIC_EnableIRQ(EXTI1_IRQn);
    NVIC_ClearPendingIRQ(EXTI2_IRQn);
    NVIC_EnableIRQ(EXTI2_IRQn);
    // enable interrupts
    __enable_irq();
} 
 
void EXTI1_IRQHandler() {
    NVIC_ClearPendingIRQ(EXTI1_IRQn); // flush pending interrupts 
    // do something here with your button... 
    EXTI->PR1 |= EXTI_PR1_PIF1; // we have processed the IRQ
} 
 
void EXTI2_IRQHandler() {
    NVIC_ClearPendingIRQ(EXTI2_IRQn); // flush pending interrupts 
    // do something here with your button... 
    EXTI->PR1 |= EXTI_PR1_PIF2; // we have processed the IRQ
} 
 
int main() {
    gpiosetup();
    intsetup();
    while(1) {
        __asm__("wfi");
    }
}
:exmp.
 
:figcap.Complete EXTI GPIO example
:efig.
:h1 id=timers.Timers
:h2 id=pwm.PWM
:h1 id=adc.ADC
:appendix.
:h1 id=biblio.Bibliography
:p.The following other books will be extensively useful in your studies:
:ul.
:li.:hp2.RM0394 Reference Manual:ehp2. -- for the following parts: 
STM32L41xxx, 42xxx, 43xxx, 44xxx, 45xxx, 46xxx
:p.STMicroelectronics. :hp1.R0394 Reference manual.:ehp1. ST Manuals, 
December 2024.
:li.:hp2.RM0090 Reference Manual:ehp2. -- for the following parts: 
STM32F405/415, STM32F407/417, STM32F427/437 and STM32F429/439
:p.STMicroelectronics. :hp1.R0090 Reference manual.:ehp1. ST Manuals, 
May 2026.
:li.:hp2.STM32L432KC Datasheet:ehp2.
:p.STMicroelectronics. :hp1.STM32L432KB, STM32L432KC.:ehp1. ST Manuals, 
May 2018.
:li.:hp2.STM32F411VE Datasheet:ehp2.
:p.STMicroelectronics. :hp1.STM32F411xC, STM32F411xE.:ehp1. ST Manuals, 
January 2024.
:eul.
:h1 id=mxproj.Creating STM32CubeMX/IDE Projects
:p.Here is an outline of steps required to create an STM32 project.
:ol prefix='setup checkoff'.
:li.Create a directory
:fn.A :q.directory:eq. is a :hp5.folder:ehp5.; this term is more 
frequently heard amongst programmers!
:efn.
in one of the following locations:
:ul.
:li.The :pk.H:\:epk. drive
:li.A flash drive
:li.:hp3.NOT:ehp3. the root of the :pk.C:\:epk. drive!!
:eul.
:li.Open :hp2.STM32CubeMX:ehp2. from the Start menu.
:li.Click :rk.File:erk., then :rk.New Project...:erk.
:li.Several dialog boxes downloading files will appear, just let those 
run.
:li.In :q.Commercial Part Number:eq., enter the STM32 model:
:ul.
:li.:pk.STM32L432KCU6:epk., for the current 3040/3050 board (the 
:q.KC:eq. board)
:li.:pk.STM32L412KBU6:epk., for the older 3040/3050 board (the 
:q.KB:eq. board)
:li.:pk.STM32F411VET6:epk., for the 2200 board
:eul.
:li.Under the :pv.Part No:epv. header in the bottom half of the screen, 
click the part number that came up.
:li.Click :rk.Start Project:erk. at the top right.
:li.Click :rk.Project Manager:erk..
:li.In :hp2.Project Name:ehp2., enter a name of your choosing.
:li.In :hp2.Project Location:ehp2., click :rk.Browse:erk. and locate 
the directory you created in Step 1.
:note.If your path starts with something that looks like 
:pv.\\sage.eng.auburn.edu\:epv., you did not properly specify the 
directory you created.
:li.Make sure :hp2.Application Structure:ehp2. is set to 
:hp2.Advanced:ehp2..
:li.Change :hp2.Toolchain/IDE:ehp2. from :rk.EWARM:erk. 
to:rk.STM32CubeIDE:erk..
:li.Uncheck the checkbox to the left of :hp2.Use Default Firmware 
Location.:ehp2.
:li.In the :hp2.Firmware Relative Path:ehp2., click :rk.Browse:erk. and 
either type in or navigate to :pk.C:\Temp\STM32CubeFirmware:epk..
:note.If this step fails, re-check the box and continue to the next 
step; you'll have to wait a few minutes to download the firmware, 
though!
:li.Click :rk.Generate Code:erk. and wait for a while.
:li.Click :rk.Open Project:erk..
:li.STM32CubeIDE will open, permitting you to continue with the rest of 
your lab.
:eol.
:h1 id=fstring.Format Specifiers
:p.These are used in the :pk.printf:epk. and :pk.scanf:epk. family of C 
library functions; only :pk.scanf:epk. is available on the STM32 target 
C library in :pk.string.h:epk..
:table cols='1i 1i *'.
:tcap.Format Specifiers
:thd.
